Republican strategy to counter Obama's reelection
Republican leaders justified their policies by the need to combat voter fraud.
The Brennan Center, however, regards the latter as a myth, claiming that voter fraud is more rare in the United States than the number of people killed by lightning.
In fact, Republican lawyers have only identified 300 cases of voter fraud in the United States in the last decade.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on participation rates.
In this sense, these measures will undermine in part the American democratic system.
Unlike in Canada, the US states are responsible for the organization of federal elections in the United States.
It is in this spirit that a majority of US governments enacted new laws beginning in 2009 that made the registration or voting process more difficult.
This phenomenon gained momentum after the November 2010 elections, which saw the addition of 675 new Republican representatives in 26 states.
As a result, 180 bills restricting the exercise of the right to vote were introduced in 41 states in 2011 alone.
New election laws require voters to present a photo ID and proof of U.S. citizenship.
These laws also shorten early voting periods, invalidate the right to register as a voter on election day, and deprive citizens with criminal records of their right to vote.
Prior to the 2006 election, no U.S. state required voters to produce a photo ID.
Indiana was the first state to make such a requirement.
The U.S. Supreme Court upheld the constitutionality of Indiana's law in 2008.
The Republican authorities were quick to extend this practice to other states.
In the last two years, they sponsored bills in 34 states to force voters to show a photo ID.
It is important to note that, unlike in Quebec, US citizens do not have a universal identity card such as the health insurance card.
In fact, 11 percent of American citizens, or 21 million people of voting age, do not have photo identification cards issued by a government agency in their state.
In addition, five million new voters in 2012 do not have such an identity document.
But it often costs more than $100 to get the required ID card.
The new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities, and low-income individuals.
Indeed, 25% of African Americans, 15% of those earning less than $35,000, 18% of citizens over the age of 65, and 20% of voters aged 18 to 29 do not have the required photo ID.
More than that.
Students, voters considered to be more likely to vote for Democratic candidates, are not allowed in several states to use their institution-issued photo ID.
On the other hand, these same states allow members of fishing or hunting clubs that vote more for the Republican side to use the cards issued by these clubs to vote.
Before 2004, no state required proof of citizenship to vote.
Arizona was the first state to introduce such a requirement.
Since 2011, a dozen states have passed laws requiring voters to prove they are U.S. citizens.
These measures are clearly aimed at limiting the Hispanic vote.
But it turns out that two out of three Hispanic voters favor the Democratic Party.
In addition, Republican lawmakers in 2011 sponsored legislation abolishing voter registration on election day in eight states.
In addition, they restricted the right of individuals and groups to provide assistance to voters seeking to register.
These restrictions are not without consequences.
For example, in the 2004 general election, voter registration campaigns helped to register some 10 million citizens.
However, the measures adopted since 2009 have reduced the registration rate of new voters in 2010 by 17% compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican lawmakers have passed laws in five other states to shorten the early voting period.
For example, in the 2008 Florida general election, 33% of voters who voted early were African-Americans, while African-Americans made up only 13% of the state's electorate.
The same was true of the Hispanics.
They represented only 11% of the electorate, but 24% of the citizens who voted in anticipation.
In contrast, whites who made up 76% of the electorate only accounted for 46% of the early voters.
Of course, Democratic legislators and their supporters have vigorously opposed the passage of laws restricting voter registration.
Several bills have been blocked by Democratic governors' vetoes.
The Attorney General of the United States intervened to suspend the most controversial laws.
They were able to contain some of the damage.
For example, only 16 of 34 states have passed laws requiring the presentation of a photo ID.
Nevertheless, the new rules that have been put in place will undoubtedly make it more difficult to exercise the right to vote in 2012.
Democratic critics denounce the partisan nature of the laws that have been passed and see them as an obvious objective to influence the results in 2012 in key states.
A 2011 Brennan Center report shows that the states that passed these laws represent 171 of the 270 electoral college votes needed to win the presidency.
It is too early to say with certainty that these legislative changes to the electoral system will have significant impacts on the outcome of the 2012 presidential elections.
But one thing is certain: these new arrangements will have a negative influence on the participation rate.
In this sense, these measures will partly undermine the American democratic system.
Prostate Cancer Screening - Should You Get It or Not?
The APS test may give false negative or false positive results, leading to unnecessary medical intervention.
This may make men who are already reluctant to take a test even more hesitant.
Pass the test or not?
We consulted two experts.
In the studies conducted in the United States, there was a lot of cross-contamination between the control groups, so it's difficult to interpret these data and make firm recommendations.
Another study, the European one, concluded that there was a difference in mortality between patients who had been screened and those who had not.
This study also showed, with a follow-up of 12 years, that you have a 30 to 40 percent higher chance of having metastases if you're not screened.
So I recommend testing at age 50, or at age 40 if you have a direct relative who's had prostate cancer.
Men of African-American descent are also at higher risk.
The key is to make the right decision once we detect cancer.
There are aggressive cancers and others that are indolent.
We really need to make the patient understand the degree of risk of their cancer, by offering them the options available, by not necessarily treating prostate cancers that do not threaten life in the long term, and by opting, in those cases, for active surveillance of the disease.
Today, many men who are diagnosed with cancer will not be treated because their cancer is not aggressive and does not threaten their lives.
We'll suggest active surveillance and if the disease progresses, we'll offer treatment.
Increasingly, criteria are being defined precisely to decide who should or should not be treated.
So I still recommend you take the test.
But the important thing is to have a discussion with his doctor to determine whether or not he should be passed.
In collaboration with the International Society of Urology, Movember has created a tool that allows the evaluation of the pros and cons of the APS test.
The document can be downloaded (in English for the time being, a translation will be available soon) at: http://ca.movember.com/fr/mens-health/prostate-cancer-screening
Preventing the disease
Unfortunately, there is no magic formula for cancer prevention.
Despite advances in research, the best way to reduce the risk of developing diabetes is to adopt healthy lifestyle habits.
It's estimated that if everyone ate right and got enough exercise, we could prevent 30 percent of cancers.
"If everyone stopped smoking, that rate would rise to at least 50 percent", says André Beaulieu, spokesman for the Canadian Cancer Society.
On the other hand, it is estimated that about 10 percent of cancers are caused by heredity.
Many also remain totally unexplained.
The Canadian Cancer Society continues to make tobacco control a priority, despite the decline in the number of smokers.
Smoking is linked to 85% of lung cancer cases.
It is also a risk factor for many others.
It's very bad for people's health.
"There are still 1.5 million smokers in Quebec", said spokesman André Beaulieu.
The encouraging fact is that 10 years after quitting, the risk of dying from cancer falls by half.
Weight
Overweight and obesity also contribute to the onset of the disease, says the CCS.
It is said to increase the risk of breast, colon and rectal cancer, esophageal, pancreatic, and uterine cancers.
"Research shows that regular physical activity throughout life is protective against colon cancer", it adds.
The food supply
The agency also recommends limiting the consumption of red meat.
Too much of it increases the risk of colorectal cancer.
So are carcasses, and they should be avoided.
The preservation of meat by smoking, drying or salting may lead to the formation of carcinogens.
"These can damage cells in the body and lead to cancer", it says.
The Vitamins
In recent years, several scientists have studied the links between vitamin supplements and cancer.
However, their research is not yet conclusive.
Studies on vitamin E are conflicting, according to the SCC.
While one showed a decrease in the risk of prostate cancer, another showed an increase.
