Mr Beaulieu also stressed the importance of discussing his concerns and family history with his doctor.
"You can't get cancer by having a blood test".
The Higgs boson peeled
The announcement of the probable discovery of the Higgs boson created quite a stir last summer, and for good reason.
It's believed that this boson is part of the mechanism responsible for the mass of everything in the universe, nothing more.
And then, it's the last particle that the Standard Model predicts exists - our best, or "least bad" explanation of the nature and behavior of matter - but has not yet been observed empirically.
But for physicists, it's not yet entirely certain that it's the Higgs.
We know without a shadow of a doubt that we're holding a genuinely new particle, and that it looks very much like the Higgs boson predicted by the Standard Model.
Furthermore, new data unveiled this week at a major physics conference in Kyoto seem to confirm this, but there is still a lack of data to be absolutely certain.
Let's assume it's the Higgs, since the chances of being wrong seem slim, and see what it is.
There is a law in this world, a law that cannot be circumvented, that two things cannot be in the same place at the same time.
There's no way to break this rule - and don't try too hard, you'll hurt yourself.
Now, even though particle physics is a very strange world, it turns out that it too has a law of this sort: the Pauli exclusion principle, which states that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantum state" - this "state" consisting roughly of some of their characteristics.
From this, physicists classify particles into two categories.
In one corner, there are good citizens called fermions, who wisely obey the principle of Pauli.
And in the other are the bosons, a dirty bunch of anarchists who have no respect for anything - at least not for this principle, which means they can be in the same place at the same time.
These bosons then split into two groups, according to the (very extraordinary) site The Particle Adventure, Berkeley Laboratories: the mesons, which we will not discuss here, and the "force particles", through which the great forces of nature propagate and to which the Higgs boson would be somehow related.
These bosons, it should be noted here, are not all as exotic beetles as you might think.
In fact, if you are able to read this column, it is because of a boson of extraordinary banality: the photon, or "particle of light", which is the "messenger" of the electromagnetic force.
When a charged particle accelerates or changes direction, it "disturbs" the electromagnetic field at that particular location, much like a pebble thrown into a pond.
From this "disturbance" comes an electromagnetic wave (from light, or infrared, or ultraviolet, etc.), and this wave is nothing but a photon - and therefore, one of the "force-carrying" bosons.
Field more stable
The same is true of the Higgs boson, except that it is another field, the Higgs field, that must be "disturbed" for this boson to appear.
Now, this Higgs field is much, much more stable than the electromagnetic field; to excite it, you have to reach very, very high energies, a bit like a frozen pond that only a very large rock could ride on.
That's why it takes a huge particle accelerator like the one at CERN - the Large Hadron Collider is a ring 17 miles in circumference! - to reach such energies.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is again useful to explain the relationship between the Higgs and mass.
Not all particles, not all materials, interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do, but others don't - a piece of paper, for example, will never hold up on its own in a fridge.
And in the same way, not all particles that interact with the Higgs field: those that do have mass, while others (like the photon, you know) don't.
Now, what "can" all this research "bring", asks Mrs Plamondon?
For science, it serves to verify the validity of the Standard Model (SM), and it also allows physicists to scrutinize any discrepancies between observations and the SM's predictions.
Many of them are very keen to find them, because the slightest difference could open the door to a "new physics" and close some holes in the Model.
It is true that the theory is still very flawed, offering no explanation for gravity (ouch!) or dark matter, which makes up about 80% of the matter in the universe (ouch!).
But we haven't found such discrepancies at CERN until now.
The consequences
The repercussions of this research on the daily lives of Mr. and Mrs. All-World are more difficult to predict, but it would be a mistake to assume that there will be none.
In the early 1960's, the laser pioneers at Bell Laboratories had no idea of the revolution their work would unleash.
They saw scientific applications, but nothing else.
In fact, we have already heard from the late physicist Willard Boyle - who worked at Bell Labs, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who himself developed the first continuous laser (the first ones were pulsed) in 1962 - that the laser was originally seen as a "lab gadget".
Can you imagine that?
And then, the applications can also come from all the instrumentation that surrounds the research.
For example, this same Willard Boyle developed a small light detector in 1969 during his work in optics.
This sensor, although not at all its original intention, now serves as the "eye" for all digital cameras in the world, and it won the 2009 Nobel Prize in Physics.
This of course doesn't mean that the activities of the LHC will necessarily transform our lives, but it does mean that, really, we never know...
Palliative care-- the best way to die-- is to have it.
With its Commission on Dying with Dignity, Quebec has recently debated the delicate issue of the end of life.
The debate is due to resume shortly as a bill is being prepared.
But in this vital area, much remains to be done.
Duty tried to look at it more closely.
Just a few weeks ago, Mr. L. was still living alone in his apartment in Montérégie.
He had two years of relief from the prostate cancer that was eating away at him.
"They gave me five years to live, I did seven", he said, half-figure, half-grape, lying in his bed at the Victor-Gadbois hospice in Beloeil, where he arrived the day before.
"But it's always a shock, you can't be prepared for it", he said.
The disease does its work: a huge weakness that prevents him from going to the toilet alone, and even eating alone.
Overwhelmed by a delicious lunch, he accepts help to eat, resigned to the situation.
Courageous, he even smiles, talks to strangers who rush around him, bring him his medication, offer him a bath.
The courage of ordinary death.
"My greatest wish is to be cured of diarrhoea, it's humiliating", he says.
A few hours later, the team found a cure for this disease.
"We learn in our lifetime that a man urinates standing up", says Pierre Brodeur, a psychologist at the Victor-Gadbois firm.
To regress to the childhood stage, for some people, is an unacceptable humiliation.
"It depends on the person's ability" to accept the regression, he says.
Because, according to many people who work in palliative care, great moments are happening at the heart of this regression.
The patients who enter the Victor-Gadbois hospice are all suffering from cancer.
They have a life expectancy of three months at most.
At this point, the team of doctors and nurses around them no longer provide so-called "curative" care.
For Mrs. A., 89, the worst fear is to die "conscious and suffocated".
But the illness has brought me to know my children.
"I have good children", she adds.
"I have no wishes in life", she said, before agreeing to be fitted with a mask to help her breathe.
She is still waiting for her son to come from Italy in the next few days.
In Victor-Gadbois, a group of volunteers provide body care and food assistance.
It's palliative care, which is given when there's nothing else to do.
To make death more comfortable.
In Quebec, there is one palliative care bed for every 11,700 inhabitants.
It's not much when you know that we're all going to die someday.
Here, life continues in the best possible conditions, explains Dr. Christiane Martel, one of the doctors of the home.
Whether it's physical comfort, emotional comfort, or spiritual comfort.
When you're dying, we'll agree to provide mouthwashes with brandy or Pepsi, depending on your request.
Diabetics will no longer have to control their sugar levels.
And death is part of the daily life.
Last night, we served a beer to Mr. X, who passed away during the night.
This morning, it's his son who'll finish the beer at the dead man's feet.
"We help the relatives as well as the patients", says Nathalie Savard, the director of the clinic.
At the Victor-Gadbois house, days follow one another but are not the same.
A 93-year-old man enjoys his last family gathering in the backyard, cuddled up in his pillows, and a toast is given to him. A 36-year-old man dies tragically, surrounded by his parents, wife and two young children, after trying everything to survive.
"In the last six months, three to five beds have been occupied by cancer patients under 45", says Dr. Christiane Martel.
53% of the patients admitted to the Victor-Gadbois home come from their homes, 47% come from the hospital.
Problems of access to palliative care
It is said that 77 percent of Canadians simply do not have access to palliative care, which is care designed to alleviate the suffering of a terminally ill patient, whether at home, in a hospital, or in a nursing home.
And several organizations, such as the Victor-Gadbois House and the Home Palliative Care Society of Greater Montreal, specialize more or less exclusively in the care of cancer patients.
It is precisely this great deficiency in Quebec health care that makes several doctors specialized in palliative care fear the adoption of a law regulating euthanasia and assisted suicide.
Since October, a manifesto signed by leading figures in palliative care, including Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapointe, has been circulating to express their opposition to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, the Quebec health system is not efficient enough to ensure that everyone will have access to quality palliative care before euthanasia is accepted.
"Recently", she said, "I saw a patient who spent 14 days in the emergency room in severe pain, without any help.
I'm afraid patients are asking to die because they're not getting the proper care.
And at the same time, several oncologists are working their patients to the last day, despite the worst prognosis.
Helen Richard's chances of survival were already slim when she abandoned the grueling chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I was stopping the treatment, she said she regretted that I stopped fighting, she said.
She said I was finished!
Not all-powerful care
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of patients who ask to die thank the caregivers for not granting their request after they have been relieved of their pain by a palliative care team.
But it must be said that palliative care is not absolutely all-powerful in treating pain.
According to Elsie Monereau, director of palliative care at the Home Palliative Society of Greater Montreal, 8 percent of patients are resistant to pain medication.
At the end of life, doctors often resort to palliative sedation, which is the practice of putting a patient to sleep until death, either sporadically or permanently.
We can't pretend we don't hear that part of the pain anymore.
More and more, the unrelieved patient is going to have the option of having this palliative sedation.
Patients who are not cured always say the same phrase: "I want to die".
But it doesn't necessarily mean "I want you to euthanize me", it means "I want to be relieved".
