Large-scale real estate scandals in Quebec
Road officials, BTP contractors, political party fundraisers and Italian mafia specialists tell day after day what they know about a formidable "system" involving the building industry, civil servants, politicians, trade unionists and mafioso.
This "industry" has been very costly for the Quebec taxpayer, especially in the 1990s and 2000s.
"It's funny how the system is falling apart since we took the big steps", quips Jacques Duchesneau, MP in Quebec and former police chief of Montreal.
It was through him that the scandal broke out in 2011, through a substantive investigation into embezzlements related to road works contracts in Quebec, to which the Liberal Prime Minister of the time, Jean Charest, had only agreed to reculons.
The "Duchesneau report" established a direct link between industry, occult funding of parties and corruption of public officials.
"Since the beginning of the investigation in 2010, the Ministry of Transport alone would have saved a billion dollars on contracts", he points out, with some holding back their instincts to grab a share!
The Charbonneau Commission "has already brought down two mayors", he added, hoping that it would be able to "demonstrate the schemes behind the individuals".
A permanent anti-corruption unit, established in 2011
The Permanent Anti-Corruption Unit, created in 2011, is also working on this with its army of government auditors, investigators and analysts.
Plus the cops from the "Hammer Squad" who, since 2009, have allegedly led the Montreal "sewage cartel" to put the pedal soft on contract swells...
In recent weeks, it has conducted a series of searches and brought fraud and corruption charges against elected officials, such as Frank Zampino and Richard Marcotte, a suburban mayor.
Next on the list would be Gilles Vaillancourt, who has just resigned as mayor of Laval, Quebec's third-largest city.
He is suspected of taking bribes repeatedly in exchange for public contracts.
The other defendants were engineers from the Montreal road works and Italian entrepreneurs, including Tony Accurso and Lino Zambito.
The latter caused a sensation by explaining to the committee the mechanics of the "system" of obtaining public contracts.
He himself paid for years 3% of the value of the contracts obtained in Montreal to an intermediary linked to the mafia who gave the money to the Union Montreal, the party of Mayor Gerald Tremblay.
Mr. Zambito was a big-time donor in the 2000s, donating more than 88,000 Canadian dollars (about $68,000) to provincial parties, mostly to the Liberals who were in power at the time.
He also confessed to organizing an illegal fundraising for the former Liberal deputy prime minister, Nathalie Normandeau.
Sewer contracts he inflated the cost of
In Montreal, the corruption "system" was working perfectly.
Gilles Surprenant, a former civil engineer, explained to the committee: in ten years, he received gifts, invitations to trips, golf tournaments, restaurants, hockey games and bribes totalling $736,000 from construction companies in exchange for contracts for sewers, the cost of which he inflated.
Other road officials have admitted that they have been greased by adding 30% to 40% to the bills, by false extras.
Then an organizer of the mayor's party, Martin Dumont, accused Mr. Tremblay of having deliberately turned a blind eye to a parallel budget that fed his coffers with dirty money.
Following these revelations, Mr. Tremblay resigned in early November, plunging Montreal into a major crisis.
Chantal Rouleau was one of the first elected officials in Montreal to sound the alarm.
Mayor of the district of Rivière-des-Prairies, in the east of the island, she has been protesting since 2010 against the sale of a municipal land bought for 5 million dollars and resold ... 1.6 million to developers, in the midst of a real estate boom.
70% of dirty money in election campaigns
Of the investigation that will eventually be set up, she says that it "shoots at a thread of understanding the workings of the system, infiltrated by ants, to stop the gangrene and pin the culprits".
The process, she says, is "painful but positive".
We're cleaning up the wound, but it would take a Montreal-based investigative unit and a watch to prevent any further suspicious practices.
How we clean up.
Regularly.
Jacques Duchesneau notes that "officials stole hundreds of millions of dollars", but is especially concerned about the role of "elected officials who knew about the scheme", when they were not stepping into the trap!
He estimates that 70% of the money used in Quebec's election campaign is dirty money. He quipped: "I was told that it was just a pale reflection of reality".
The Quebec government proposes to limit donations to political parties to $100 but this will not change the situation, he says: "As long as we do not strictly limit electoral expenditure, there will be dirty money in politics".
He advocates a complete overhaul of the public procurement and party funding system: "We cannot go any lower; going to the bottom of things, with courage, will allow us to rebuild the house on a stronger foundation, with more controls and laws".
If this story tarnishes the international image of Quebec and Montreal, Mr. Duchesneau invites those who laugh to look in their own courtyard...
