With Bitcoin, you can pay and sell without banks
This is the exact opposite of today's monetary exchanges, which are based on central banks, identified transactions and processing fees between stakeholders.
Moreover, as is often the case with these technologies, a political vision is evident: the belief that the current monetary system, made up of banking monopolies, leads to financial crises.
In fact, Bitcoin, invented by Satoshi Nakamoto (a pseudonym), is both a virtual currency (but convertible to dollars, euros, etc.) and a secure exchange protocol in the manner of BitTorrent, which allows the exchange of peer-to-peer files.
About 200,000 transactions have already been recorded by 15,000 computers on the network.
A few thousand websites accept bitcoins as donations or as payment.
The bitcoin price, after reaching a peak of $30 (€23) in June 2011, fell to $2 five months later, before returning to around $10 today (the prices are listed on the bitcoincharts.com website).
Not much to be impressed by, compared to the world's trade in real money or financial products.
However, the European Central Bank (ECB) has taken an interest in this in a report on virtual currencies published in October.
It describes bitcoin as "the most successful virtual currency", "competing with the dollar or the euro" and "similar to conventional currencies".
Bitcoin is distinct from other types of virtual currency such as "credits", which are used to advance in a video game that you earn by playing or that you can buy (and sometimes exchange in return).
Facebook has also developed such a system.
But each time, a central authority controls and processes the exchanges.
With Bitcoin, all nodes in the network are at once bookkeepers, auditors, issuers of currency, and buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Every transaction between two users is actually between two email addresses in the same way as an email.
Except a user can choose a different address for each payment, thus ensuring anonymity.
A set of information related to this transaction is electronically signed by a double-key encryption system.
The network can then verify the authenticity of the transaction.
The contents of the file also make it possible to ensure that the exchanged bitcoins actually exist in the public ledger, which is distributed throughout the network.
The key step is to write this new transaction in this book.
It involves solving a mathematical challenge to computers, and the winner, a sort of temporary central banker, will have the privilege of adding this extra line.
This is a file hashing phase, i.e. the transformation of a large file into a shorter and unique digital footprint.
The computers "take" the new transaction and add a number to it before "hacking" the whole.
The goal is to find the number that gives a particular imprint (many zeros at the beginning).
Once that number is found, the other nodes can easily verify that it is the right one.
The transaction is then indestructibly linked to the chain of all other transactions; any modification would change the imprint.
If, for fraud, a user wanted to pay twice with the same money very quickly (less than ten minutes), only one of the two transactions would be validated by the network - the other being orphaned because the two have different fingerprints.
The computer that solves the challenge wins 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, this reward is divided by two regularly, probably before the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is therefore limited to 21 million, but they are divisible up to a hundred millionth, which leaves a margin...
The difficulty of the challenge is also raised with each increase in computing power.
Life on the network has had its ups and downs.
Websites providing services for Bitcoin have been attacked and bitcoins in deposits stolen.
"The flaw is not in the protocol itself", says Pierre Noizat, who has just launched Paymium, a company that uses the Bitcoin network to make payments in real currency.
The ECB also mentions the possibilities of money laundering through this anonymous service.
But cash also has this defect.
Big players like Wikipedia are refusing donations of this nature.
Others, such as the WordPress blogging platform, accept them.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron, from the Weizmann Institute in Israel, analyzed the ledger and showed that nearly 80 percent of bitcoins are not in circulation.
In November, "giant sales" were launched.
"Thirty thousand dollars were exchanged", says Jon Holmquist, who works for Coinabul, which converts bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noizat, who has also written a textbook on the currency, believes strongly in the potential of this technology as a network of transactions.
Its system, Paytunia, is the equivalent of a credit card (in real currency) or a contactless mobile payment, but it uses Bitcoin to validate transactions, which are cheaper.
The wearer also manages his identity and can therefore be anonymous.
The system is easy to implement for merchants, who do not need to install new terminals or software.
All they have to do is provide an address that a phone can "photograph and recognize", says Pierre Noizat, who claims to have thousands of users.
There is a general movement away from hierarchical systems towards more horizontal ones.
"It will take time for Bitcoin to gain traction, but 2013 could be a turning point", he predicts.
The ECB, in its report, also plans to reassess the various risks, which are now considered high, in the event of a success of this currency.
