A Constitution at the Grip in Egypt
This is another poker move by President Mohammed Morsi.
With Egypt more divided than ever over the constitutional declaration, which temporarily grants him full powers, he decided to play it cool.
He took everyone by surprise when he announced on Wednesday that the Constituent Assembly would vote on its final text the next day.
The President of the Republic has given this Assembly two more months to complete its work.
For almost two years, Egypt has been relying on a provisional text, amended several times, which weakens institutional stability and leads to legal tricks.
This new initiative has only increased the fracture in the country.
Opponents say the president is still "a self-appointed madman", continuing to "betray his word" and "trample on the law".
The supporters of the new government claim that it is a way of ending the institutional and political crisis as quickly as possible, by speeding up the transition process.
A referendum should be held within two weeks.
A very short period of time that forced the Brothers to abandon their project of explaining the text, article by article, to the Egyptians.
For the president, it is also a way to regain popular and democratic legitimacy while the contestation rages throughout the country.
Mohammed Morsi seems confident that the Egyptians will vote in favour, as he stated in an interview with the American weekly Time.
This is especially so as the rushed vote is an ultimatum to the Egyptian people: "Either you vote for my text or I keep my full powers", which are supposed to end after the adoption of the Constitution.
It is in a strange atmosphere that 85 members of this constituent assembly, with a large majority of Islamists, voted for the text yesterday.
Most of the Liberals were absent from the call.
In mid-November, shortly before the constitutional declaration, they had slammed the door, feeling that they could not assert their views.
The same was true of representatives of human rights, religious minorities and civil society.
In order to reach the necessary quorum, 11 members, substitutes, were added hastily yesterday morning.
Some are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
Unsurprisingly, most articles were voted unanimously.
Commentators have also mocked the fact that one of the only differences of opinion of the day was expressed around the time of prayer, some members of the committee felt that the clock of the constituent was badly adjusted.
The text, which was still being voted on last night, contains 234 articles.
Despite all the attention, Article 2 is finally identical to that of the 1971 Constitution, stating that "the principles of the sharia are the main source of law".
Salafist parties, for whom the establishment of Islamic law is a major demand, hoped to replace "principles" with "rules", which would have allowed for stricter enforcement.
For the Islamists, the fact that this article has not been changed is a sign of their goodwill and respect for other components of Egyptian society.
"Hypocrisy", say the Liberals, who see it as a simple communication ploy.
Because they think the Islamization of the Constitution is done through other articles.
They are particularly concerned about Article 220, which gives Al-Azhar University an advisory role, in particular in verifying the conformity of laws with the Sharia.
Egyptologist Sophie Pommier says this is worrying because "people who are called to speak are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
It is the beginning of a theocracy".
The Liberals' fears are further fuelled by the fact that the next rector of this university should be far less moderate than the current one.
"At this time, there is no concrete religious implication.
With this Constitution, we remain within the framework of the civil state.
Most of the jurists who worked on this text are not ulema but academics, some of them trained in the French system", says Alexis Blouet, who is preparing a thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
But he acknowledges that "there may be ambiguity about Article 220, because the terms used are borrowed from religious vocabulary.
References to "fiqh" are included.
And the question may be raised in the future as to the extent to which civil judges are competent to rule on them".
Beyond its religious aspect, the text voted yesterday is heavily criticised because of the extensive powers it grants to the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood argues that these are markedly reduced compared to what they were under the old regime.
Another point of contention was the powers granted to the army.
In accordance with the wishes of the military, the Defence budget will not be submitted to Parliament, but to a National Defence Council.
Nor will civilians be barred from military trials, as human rights groups have demanded.
The latter also express their concerns about the text, which they consider to be liberticidal.
The offense of blasphemy is maintained and insult is now prohibited, which could have serious consequences for freedom of expression, including freedom of the press.
Moreover, no article is more in line with the protection of women, said Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
According to her, the only positive point is the prohibition of torture by Article 36.
The word was not in the previous Constitution.
While the Egyptian president was supposed to speak on television last night, demonstrations are planned for this afternoon.
The supporters of the head of state will march on Saturday.
In Israel, holy places, the center of the world and a sea of brine await Ukrainian tourists
The Promised Land combines the grandeur of Bible truths, modern conveniences, and wildlife.
Argoumenty i Fakty has picked five big reasons to go to Israel.
Go worship at the holy places
A must-see: the banks of the Jordan River where Jesus was baptized.
It is said that anyone who enters these "baptism pools" will be touched by divine grace.
Galilee is the land of Jesus' miracles - where he turned water into wine, where he walked on water, where he calmed the wind, and where he miraculously caught fish.
It was in this very place that Jesus appeared to his disciples after his resurrection.
But where you will find the most holy places is in Jerusalem.
The believers walk along the Street of Suffering, or the Way of the Cross (Latin: Via Dolorosa).
This path starts near the Antonia Fortress (the Praetorium), where the trial was held, then leads through the streets of the Old City to the Church of the Holy Sepulchre on Golgotha, to the place of the Crucifixion, then to the place of the Anointing Stone and the burial.
This is the Christian world center, the symbol of the salvation of mankind.
According to Christian legend, the Monastery of the Cross is built on the site where the tree used to make the cross on which Jesus was crucified grew.
It also houses the holiest place of the Jews, the Wailing Wall, which is the remnant of a temple destroyed by the Romans in 70 BC.
Tradition has it that people of different faiths leave small notes with prayers that are then answered.
Traveling high
Visit the ruins of the fortress of Massada, a former refuge from enemies built by Herod the Great in 25 B.C. for his family.
These ruins are on the steep rocks of a mountain at 450 m above sea level.
Only those who love mountaineering can reach it on their own.
For others, a cable car takes them to this summit of history.
In the north of the country, between 1 600 and 2 040 m above sea level, is the ski resort of Mount Hermont, which is visited by many tourists in winter.
A shuttle can take you there from the foot of the mountain.
The ski slopes are a total of 45 km long.
Old beliefs say that pagan gods once dwelt on the top of the mountain.
Visiting Unique Museums
This country has nearly 300 museums.
It's impossible to visit all of them in one trip.
Here are five of the most interesting ones that are definitely worth checking out.
First, the Israel Museum, located near the Knesset (parliament).
It contains the very ancient Qumran manuscripts, or Dead Sea Scrolls, discovered in the caves of the Judean Desert, as well as nearly half a million archaeological and anthropological artifacts.
See also: Tel Aviv Museum of Art
The main exhibited works are those by the Impressionists and the Expressionists - Monet, Pissarro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall, and Picasso.
In Acre, Hammam Al-Basha awaits you with its Turkish baths made up of casts of visitors and guards of the time.
Once in Caesarea, enter the unique private Ralli Museum where you can admire Rodin's sculptures.
There are no guidebooks or souvenir shops.
Admission is free and donations are prohibited.
The fifth museum is the Yad Vashem Holocaust Museum or Memorial, located in Tel Aviv, which revisits the most dramatic historical pages of history.
The most tragic part is the Children's Memorial, built in memory of the 1.5 million children who were exterminated in the concentration camps and gas chambers.
You go in and you go into total darkness.
The stars are twinkling.
Then you hear the names of the Jewish children and the names of the countries in which they died.
Ukraine is also mentioned.
Health and well-being
Israel's three major seaside resorts are located on the shores of the Mediterranean Sea, the Red Sea, and the Dead Sea.
Each of these islands has swimming pools, water parks, dolphinariums, and giant aquariums.
Note: You can swim in the Red Sea even in winter, as the water temperature does not drop below 21°C, while the air temperature can reach 23°C.
The Dead Sea is even warmer, and you can swim in it all year long.
By the way, this is the world's most unique sea, occupying the lowest point on Earth, 417 meters below sea level.
The blue water contains brine and easily holds swimmers, even those who cannot swim.
The landscapes around it are surreal in beauty.
People come to the temple for treatment with salt water, lime, and curative mud, and for various ailments such as dermatitis, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, and diabetes, as well as for relaxation.
Unlock the Secrets of the Ancient World
They are guarded by the old city of Tel Aviv, Jaffa, on the shores of the Mediterranean Sea.
It is crossed by the famous Via Maris, which connects Egypt, Syria, Anatolia, and Mesopotamia.
The city is mentioned in ancient Greek and Egyptian legends.
According to legend, it was here that Noah built his ark and that Perseus saved the beautiful Andromeda, with whom he lived a long and happy life here.
Tourists especially enjoy walking along the narrow alleys named after the zodiac signs.
They say that if you touch the walls of the street that correspond to your sign, fate will smile on you.
In Jaffa you can meet newlyweds who have come to take photos from all over Israel and even other countries.
In Caesarea, the city of King Herod, you can stroll through the Roman theater, "conquering" the Crusader fortress.
Under the Roman Empire, Caesarea was the principal city of Judea and the residence of Roman procurators, including Pontius Pilate.
The carefully restored theater is now used for evening concerts and opera performances.
Note to tourists
If you go to Israel, don't worry about your English: about 30% of the population speaks Russian.
For your travel, it is better to prefer dollars to euros, since they are easily exchanged for shekels (today 1 dollar equals 3.8 shekels).
In terms of urban transport, the main means of transport are buses, but Jerusalem has a fast tram and Haifa has the only metro line in the country, consisting of six stations and capable of connecting the lower and upper parts of the city.
It's almost like an underground cable car.
The journey in all types of public transport costs 6 shekels and allows you to make changes for 1 hour 30.
In Israel, the Jewish tradition requires the Sabbath to be kept on Saturday.
From Friday night until sundown on Saturday, markets, shops and public transportation are closed.
And the work week starts on Sunday morning.
Many cafes, restaurants, and hotels serve only kosher food, which excludes pork, seafood, shellfish, and dishes that include both milk and meat.
It offers a wide range of dishes made from lamb and beef, soups and desserts made from coconut milk, as well as hummus, traditional Jewish dough, various sauces, ground chick pea balls, falafel, fruit and vegetables.
There are no stray dogs in the streets of Israeli cities.
On the other hand, many well-fed cats walk around with a haughty air.
You can see them sleeping on the roofs of parked cars at night.
These cats like to be in the open and they don't mind being tamed.
The price of a car rental varies depending on the brand from $37 for 24 hours (Hyundai Getz) to $188 (Audi A6, Volvo S80).
Insurance costs $15 a day.
Renting a bicycle will cost you 15 shekels a day.
The average price of admission to the museum is 30 shekels.
The Language of Numbers
Three million tourists from around the world visited Israel in 2012.
These were mostly people who came to travel and rest from the United States, Russia, France, Germany, Italy, England and Ukraine.
118.8 thousand Ukrainian tourists visited the Promised Land from January to October 2012, which is 51% more than in 2010, before the cancellation of visas on February 9, 2011.
"Who has a language, goes to Moscow": migrants save money to learn the language
While MPs and human rights activists debate what the law on the compulsory language test will bring, fraudsters selling "fake" certificates have already appeared in the country.
Each year, 13 million migrant workers come to Moscow, St. Petersburg and other Russian cities.
Most of them are nationals of Central Asia: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
Their only goal is to earn money to help their families back home.
Since December 1, a law came into force that states that every migrant worker will have to pass an examination in Russian.
At present, this rule applies only to those intending to work in the service, housing, personal services and retail sectors.
However, in time, promises the Federal Migration Service, testing will become mandatory for all immigrants.
In addition, it will be necessary to validate the knowledge of the language, but also the knowledge of Russian history and the foundations of law.
You will need to validate your knowledge of Russian in order to obtain and renew your work permit.
Only nationals of countries where Russian is an official language are exempted.
The law also does not apply to persons who obtained teaching certificates or diplomas before the collapse of the USSR in 1991.
Benefit, negative attitude and protection of rights
The network of examination centres will be under the auspices of the Pushkin Institute of Russian Language, the Peoples' Friendship University, the Moscow State University, the St. Petersburg State University and other higher education institutions in Russia.
Immigrants will be able to take the exams in all cities in the country: more than 160 centres have already been opened throughout the country.
This initiative to introduce examinations was supported by the State Duma and the Federal Migration Service.
But before the law comes into force, human rights defenders have already asked the question many times in the press: what will happen?
What will the requirement to know Russian change for Russians and immigrants?
Firstly, say the migration service, it will reduce the number of people suffering from "work slavery".
Many speak about defending the rights of migrant workers, says the director of the Russian Federal Migration Service's office in Tajikistan, Victor Sebelev.
The protection of rights must begin before they leave.
Only an organized selection system will solve 90% of the problems of foreign workers.
The problems arise for migrants without a profession, without training, those who do not know the language and who do not have medical certificates.
Without understanding the language, Sebelev says, the would-be migrant is destined to meet dishonest people who, under the guise of helping, will provide him with a "trip" to a crowded house where he and dozens of his fellow migrants will suffer for months without food and paper and have to toil 12 to 14 hours a day.
We receive many complaints from our migrants.
"They are promised something, and when they arrive, they are deceived, their passports are taken, and they do not get the salary", confirms the Head of the Directorate of Migration Services for Work of the Migration Service of Tajikistan, Tolib Charipov.
Don't argue with me, officer!
However, many nationals from the Central Asian republics who wish to come to Russia to earn money say that they not only do not know the language of the country they wish to visit, but also have difficulty writing in their own language.
It is not their fault, of course, but their misfortune that few Turkmen, Uzbeks and Tajiks can afford to have even a decent primary education.
Their families do not even have enough to feed their children, let alone to dress them properly and equip them for school.
As soon as they reach adolescence, these youngsters go to earn money as soon as the opportunity arises.
It's hard when you don't know the language, they say.
"You feel diminished and diminished".
However, human rights defenders note an important aspect of the language law.
The examinations will be intended only for migrants with legal status.
Without status, there will be no exam or formal work afterwards.
However, most migrant workers continue to live in Russia illegally.
"Welcome or not welcome"
Many immigrants explain that it is not so easy to get official status in Russia.
The reason? The administrative barriers and always those language difficulties.
Moreover, legalization costs money: between 12 and 16 thousand rubles.
Besides, you can get a fake recording fast for only 1,500 rubles.
The Russian cops know we have fake documents, we don't have a record, hence the extortion cases.
"They ask us for 100, 200 rubles, to buy cigarettes, tea", said Oumed Khouchkadamov, a citizen of Tajikistan, to the reporters.
"Hurry, don't skimp and buy yourself a fine work of art"
On the first day of the language law's entry into force, it was discovered that the immigrant registration papers were not the only ones that were fake.
Several forged language examination certificates have already been confiscated by employees of the Federal Migration Service.
The forged papers come out of a regular color printer.
Of course, their new owners did not get them for nothing: each migrant who hoped to facilitate the examination had to pay seven thousand rubles for this document.
It is two and a half times more expensive than the official procedure: it will cost the migrant worker three thousand rubles.
Government officials and human rights defenders agree that the short-term goal is to protect the system against corruption so that it is impossible to simply buy these "paper clippings".
The authorities may give migrant workers who were unable to pass the examination in the first place time to take language courses.
Moreover, immigrants who do not know Russian will be offered jobs in fields that do not involve active communication with people.
The Ministry of the Interior is not in charge of the arms market.
The share of crimes involving legal weapons is very low
The Russian Ministry of Interior is proposing to tighten the law against civilian gun owners.
This is the reaction of the authorities to recent incidents, from shootings at weddings to the massacre organized by the Moscow lawyer Dmitry Vinogradov, which left seven dead.
Police want to ban the carrying of rubber bullets in public places and raise the legal age for a gun license from 18 to 21.
The idea was supported by the head of the Duma Committee for Security and Anti-Corruption, Irina Yarovaya who promised that the amendments to the Arms Law will be introduced in the State Duma soon.
Not everyone is happy that the Russian authorities are trying to solve the problem by "screwing the screws".
An open letter has appeared on the Net in which the authors, representatives of various shooting centers, demanded to abandon "this senseless hardening".
The percentage of crimes committed with a registered weapon is minimal, Vasiliy Lesnikov, a lawyer and crime specialist for the BBC, told the Russian service.
According to the statistics of the Ministry of Interior, in a six-month period in 2012, 142 crimes were committed with a registered firearm in the police services while 1,168 thousand crimes were recorded in the same period.
The authors of the open letter are confident that the strengthening of the laws on civilian weapons will not prevent criminals from sourcing from the black market.
According to them, today in Moscow you can find any weapon for a reasonable price.
However, the Ministry of Interior claims that it controls the spread of illegal weapons.
Suppliers: from factory to officer
The black market for weapons is supplied through several channels.
The main channels are five, says Victor Baranets, a retired colonel who served for ten years in the Ministry of Education and the General Staff.
Screenshot from a website taking orders for weapons
The first is "the military trace", i.e. weapons that were stolen during military operations in the Caucasus.
"These weapons were stolen by Russian officers, but also by Caucasians", Baranets explains.
The second type of black market weapons are those stolen from law enforcement by criminals.
Baranets explains that these are both weapons stolen from the police stock and those stolen directly from law enforcement representatives.
Illegal guns are coming out of military warehouses.
Many of these have been the victims of explosions.
"According to the accounts, some fires were set deliberately to cover up the deficit", the former military official said.
Baranets thinks the gun manufacturers are behind it.
"Private arms factories that are not competitive on the international market are selling arms on the black market, especially in Moscow", says one expert.
Another source of black market is smuggling.
A large share of guns and machine guns come from poor countries, such as Kyrgyzstan.
"There is a local production, sometimes handmade, a mafia has formed and organizes the supply", adds the former military.
Where did the guns come from?
The experts have estimated the approximate share of each source of illegal weapons on the black market.
A report on the issue was produced in 2011 by the Centre for Problem Analysis and Study for Public Administration.
Specialists analyzed reports from the Ministry of Interior and Rosstat, criminal records and public data from gun websites.
The vast majority of illegal weapons, say researchers, come from the military and law enforcement.
Half of the guns on the black market ended up there "because of employees whose work is related to guns", says the report.
According to the researchers, 17% of the weapons come from places of military conflict, 14% are stolen at the time of manufacture and 5% come from "clandestine searches".
A salesman and consultant for a weapons factory who asked to remain anonymous assures that for a long time no one buys the weapons found by these specialists in the clandestine search; they are too old.
Most of the time, he says, the salesmen go to the military warehouses to get the new merchandise.
The person purchases a unit, for example a TT pistol, through a trade mark.
We deliver it to him by passing the goods through a grate.
"He takes it to the city and sells it for €900 per unit with two chargers", he says.
"It is true that the police are aware of all the cases, so when crimes are about to be solved, they make a control purchase from the illegal arms dealers", the salesman adds.
" Like in a luxury shop "
The seller and the buyer are usually found through acquaintances.
I consulted websites, blogs, until a guy showed up and offered to come to the Begovaya station where someone was going to take me to a "corner" to bargain.
The price of the gun, I was given it on the spot
Victor Baranets as a military observer
To find a gun, I have to know someone who has a contact, the salesman explains.
There are vendors in the markets, but there you also have to come and say for example "From such and such person, who asked me to pass on that his daughter lost a tooth".
Now I even buy a pair of American fists with the help of someone I trust.
He only gives them to me because he knows I won't give it to him.
The new kids look for weapons in different ways.
Former military officer Victor Baranets tried his hand as a buyer of illegal weapons in the mid-1990s when he was preparing to publish a paper on the subject.
The patterns, he said, haven't changed.
We gave him a photo album that had "everything we wanted" in it.
"I thought I was in a luxury boutique", the soldier recalls.
There are no secrets for the buyer, Baranets explains, everything can be tried.
As a potential customer, I don't just buy, we go with the seller in the woods and set up a target.
"They let me shoot and when I am convinced that the weapon works well, we start negotiating", the expert explains.
A shop from her couch
Search engines show the sites and groups on Vkontakte where you can buy weapons "for different uses".
You don't need any documents or anyone to meet.
"All you need is a certain amount of money", says an advertisement on the "Buy a Fighting Pistol or Machine Gun" website.
Users leave their requests and ask their questions.
And sell to the miners?
"Without permission, of course", asks the user "Ivan" (spelling is preserved).
"Buy TT. Moscow", writes "Fedorenkov" in his very direct request.
The Federal Security Service has spread a vast network of fake websites and is scooping up people who want to buy combat weapons.
People rush for food like hungry wolves and then they end up mining coal in Siberia.
Victor Baranets, observer and former military
I've heard of these types of schemes: usually, the site is registered outside the scope of Russian law.
