At the meeting of the Committee on Budgetary Control in the Chamber of Deputies you mentioned a Czech-German project in which the public procurement laws of the two countries were compared.
What was the specific issue?
This is a parallel control that we launched about two years ago.
In simple terms, European legislation provides for the way in which public contracts are managed and specific national legislation and practice follow.
We have gathered all this together and although this control procedure is not yet complete, some very interesting differences have emerged: in general terms our legislation may be 'more stringent and of better quality', but in some parameters the practice as such is better in Germany.
This confirms that it is not enough to constantly develop more and more detailed rules, but that it is necessary to focus on the actual application of the law.
How can this project help you in practical terms and what does it mean for you?
A common control of this kind should help us to stop trying to specify the laws, to lower and improve the thresholds, when this does not have a really positive effect.
The principle of good management means obtaining the thing in question at a reasonable price (which does not always mean the lowest price), in order to exclude any enrichment and possible criminal activity.
But lowering the thresholds of the markets will not necessarily achieve this objective.
It may be that this system is so overwhelmed by paperwork that those who seek to find fault with it will find many more opportunities than if the threshold had remained higher.
