Poland and the cosmos.
Last week, at the meeting of ministers of the European Space Agency, Poland was admitted as the 20th member of the agency, the second member state of the former Eastern bloc (the Czech Republic became a full member on 12 November 2008).
Poland began close cooperation with ESA in 1994 and in the years since has participated in a number of ESA projects.
Poland's road to space, however, began much earlier.
Even before World War II, passionate Poles were working on spaceflight; they did not always meet with understanding.
I would like to mention, for example, the lecture given by A. Šternfeld at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory on 6 December 1933, in which he presented ideas from his groundbreaking work "Introduction to Astronautics".
The developments of this young engineer (born in 1905) left listeners cold and years later Šternfeld remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomski was interested in his work.
In 1934, Šternfeld was awarded the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch Prize in France for his work "Introduction to Astronautics".
The late Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became a great proponent of astronomy and astronautics.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish newspapers and wrote many books on this scientific discipline.
Gadomski became a world-renowned proponent of astronautics, and his contribution was rewarded by the fact that one of the craters on the far side of the Moon was named after him.
As early as 1925 a draisin was built in Poland to be equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, we do not know the author or the details of this project.
It is also unclear whether the rocket was intended to propel or slow down the drainage.
The only information known about this draisine is that of the press of the time.
From 1933 onwards, the Polish artillery began to focus on rockets.
The research was conducted by the Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia Institute in collaboration with Professors Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Gustaw Mokrzyckiego.
It is clear from the archives that this research has reached the testing stage.
Of course, with the arrival of the German armies, the search was interrupted.
In 1937 plans of a photoelectric fighter rocket, drawn by engineer Rohoziński, appeared in the specialized press and the following year the book "Rakieta - torpeda powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza" by an author named Leliwy-Krzywoblocki was published.
Both projects were designed for military use of rocket engines.
Just before the war, all the projects for the use of rocket technology were carried out by the Provisional Scientific Advisory Committee ("Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy"), which coordinated all the work.
This committee was set up in 1937, but after two years of operation, the outbreak of the war brought its activities to an end.
After the war, other works on aeronautics were published in the Polish press, thanks to the Polish Astronautical Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
For the first time, a company was mentioned in the November 1954 issue of the journal Problème, which contained four more detailed articles on aeronautics.
In one of these articles, written by Professor M. Subotowicze, it is proposed to create a society devoted to the study of space.
By this time, artificial satellite projects had already been launched, and it was clear that the field of space research had a future.
At the beginning of 1956, the Polish Astronautical Society (PTA) made efforts to enter the International Astronautical Federation (created in 1951) and as of autumn, the PTA became a regular member.
The following year, the first president of the PTA, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902-1959), became vice-president of the International Astronautical Federation.
He held the post until his death in 1959.
From 1956, the PTA made a significant contribution to the successful development of the RM (Rakieta Meteorologiczna) weather rocket, which became the first Polish rocket to carry out scientific research.
The first model, RM-1, was completed in 1957 and the first launch took place on 10 October 1958.
This rocket with a range of 1800 meters had a length of 80 cm and weighed a little less than 5 kg.
An improved version, RM-1A, was subsequently built, and in the summer of 1959, flight tests of the two-stage RM-2 rocket began in the Bledov Desert.
This rocket was about four and a half feet long and weighed about 30 pounds.
The next prototype should have been capable of performing concrete scientific work - the RM-34 rocket should have had a range of up to 14.5 km and be used to observe the wind at altitude.
But in 1963 all development work was halted.
The Meteor-1 rocket developed during the period 1962 - 1965, succeeded the first RM rockets.
This two-stage rocket had a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three models (called Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed; they were distinguished by the dimensions of the space reserved for scientific tools.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a space offering a volume of 0.4 liters, while in Meteor-1B this volume was 0.34 liters and in Meteor-1C 0.62 liters.
The maximum range of all these types of craft was 23 miles.
In the period 1965 - 1968, the Meteor-2 rockets were developed in the aeronautical institute, the first flight tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had an initial weight of 380 kg and was capable of carrying a payload of 10 kg at an altitude of about 60 km.
Later, the Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were built.
Poland joined the Committee for Space Research (COSPAR) in 1960 and a national committee was set up two years later.
Poland also participated in space exploration on Soviet artificial satellites as part of the Interkosmos program, and in 1978 pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became the second non-Soviet cosmonaut in the program after Vladimír Dans Remek.
