The movie Argo: when things go wrong, call Hollywood.
In November 1979, a mob of Islamist student protesters stormed the U.S. Embassy in Tehran and took 52 diplomats hostage.
They were to be released in exchange for the Shah, Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, who, after the revolution, had fled to the United States, which had supported his regime for several decades.
The situation did not offer the US administration a positive outcome, it could not, in fact, abandon the Shah, because it would have seriously shaken the confidence of its allies in other countries.
However, in Iran, where the revolution had led to the establishment of a theocratic regime, the revolution was unable to secure the release of the hostages.
It was a blow to the prestige of the United States, which was later aggravated by the fiasco of the attempt to free the hostages by force.
The hostages were finally released 444 days later, following negotiations organized by the Algerian government.
Their fate has sparked a wave of solidarity and anti-Iranian sentiment in the United States.
The Iranian debacle contributed greatly to Jimmy Carter's defeat by Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential election.
The movie Argo, by actor and director Ben Affleck, depicts an episode of this story that offers a small victory to America.
Just before it was occupied, six employees escaped from the embassy.
After a complicated series of events, they met at the Canadian ambassador's residence.
Working with Canadian authorities, the CIA managed to get them out of Iran under a ruthless cover: they left the country with Canadian passports as part of a film crew scouting for a science fiction blockbuster.
Gender combined
The plan of the exfiltration expert Tony Mendez required the collaboration of Hollywood.
To make the legend more credible, specialized magazines reported on the film project, press conferences were organized, and a fictitious production company had real offices.
The details of the operation were kept secret for a long time, as the film was based on the memories of Tony Mendez.
Affleck's film is an unusual combination of several genres.
It is part of a realistically conceived political thriller but also a "caper movie", the story of a successful coup, of a betrayal - as, for example, in the trilogy Ocean's eleven, twelve and thirteen.
The ambiance is one after another: footage of Tehran in documentary style (in the subtitled footage are presented iconic photographs of the time of the events and the way, thanks to these photos, these same situations were transcribed in the film, there are no major differences),
lighter passages from Hollywood, treated with irony and a bit of exaggeration,
And then there are scenes from CIA headquarters and other institutions with men in costumes discussing the situation around conference tables, in hallways and on the phone...
Ben Affleck has managed to restart his career in a remarkable way.
From a derisive actor, he became a respected director, and his acting no longer provoked sarcastic remarks.
Argo is her third feature film after the dark police drama Gone Baby Gone (2007) and the thriller The Town (2010).
It is also Affleck's first film not to be set in his hometown of Boston.
The sense of the atmosphere of a place is one of the characteristics that placed his first films above the Hollywood standards.
Affleck also shows this sense of atmosphere in Argo where the role of Tehran is "held" by Canada.
The best scenes of the film take place in the streets, during the reconstruction of real events; the initial sequence of the fall of the embassy is impressive for its clarity which also suggests the confusion and unpredictability that occurs when suddenly, in a given place, a page of history is written.
Affleck and his collaborators achieve a similar effect in the fictional scenes (the fake film crew in the Tehran bazaar).
Too many actions in too many places
The director had to settle for a subject that offered few thrilling scenes, in the cinematic sense of the term.
He does it very well, sometimes adding some elements to reality and here, the result is not always so elegant (the scene in which the threat of crisis at Tehran airport is removed by a phone call in America and the pursuit on the landing strip is quite drawn by the hair).
Argo's weakness lies in its dissipative nature, due to the need to show too many events in too many different places.
While it's true that Alan Arkin and John Goodman are quite charming in their role as Hollywood cooperators, their characters would have deserved a bigger role and they are by no means the only ones.
Affleck's film lacks a little dramatic tension, and is seen with a moderate interest, appreciating the direction and retro style of the 70s.
He's drawing the viewer, but with difficulty.
As a reminder of a story that is still, in some ways, unfinished to this day, and as an illustration of the exaggerated nature of the portrayal of the secret services as omnipotent and omniscient, it does the job.
Rules for inflating balloons, bananas and the circus
The www.bankovnipoplatky.com server, which annually conducts a public survey of the most absurd bank charges, has now decided to launch the competition of the most absurd settlement or ideas from the "EU workshop".
"The fact that the EU is considering, in recent times, to adopt a quota of 40 per cent of women for the management of large European companies was the origin of our decision", said the organizer of this survey, Patrik Nacher, to the newspaper Právo.
The absurdities mentioned already include, for example, the recent decision of the European Court of Justice to unify insurance premiums for men and women.
Until now, however, women have been better off in terms of life insurance rates because they are objectively less of a risk to insurance companies.
People can report until the end of the year any other such incredible idea of "EU workshop".
"The vote will take place before the end of February 2013", Nacher said.
Controversial EU regulations include, for example, the requirement to add components to biofuels, which has harmful consequences for the environment, the ban on the use of reliable mercury thermometers, simply because they contain a relatively small amount of a dangerous substance, or the directive on the size of chicken cages, which has led to an increase in the price of eggs.
Criticism has also been voiced in the past against the de facto ban on the use of the term 'tanning butter' or the withdrawal of conventional light bulbs.
The quality bananas must be 14 centimeters in size.
The European administration often reacts under pressure from a commercial or industrial lobby whose demands are usually defended in Brussels by a state or group of states (so the Czech Republic is currently imposing the demands of its banks by threatening to use its veto).
The interests of pressure groups are also behind, for example, the fact that in the Union bananas must not be less than 14 cm tall or have an 'abnormal curve'.
The European Commission defended itself by arguing that it was merely harmonising non-homogeneous national standards which complicated trade.
The standards for fruit and vegetables have been relaxed despite the opposition of some States, who claim that the existing directives lead to food waste.
The first prize in this survey may be awarded to last year's EU regulation that inflatable balloons must have a warning on them that children under 8 years of age should not inflate them without adult supervision.
The EU referred to an American survey which showed that among toys, balloons are the leading cause of death in children from suffocation.
A similar restriction applies to children under 14 years of age when blowing into carnival trumpets.
We have some strange ideas in our house too.
The following rule regarding European officials themselves is quite absurd: due to the sensitivity of this topic for Greece, anyone holding an official position within the EU cannot use the name "Macedonia" and must instead speak of FYROM (Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia).
In collaboration with the association "Laissez Faire" of liberal economists, Bankovnípoplatky.com server named in this survey, in addition to some of the absurdities mentioned above, the EU regulation on the volume of food stocks on the territory of the Czech Republic.
The EU had set maximum quantities for food stocks that could be found on the territory of the Czech Republic on the day of our accession to the EU.
The Czech Republic, for example, subsequently exceeded the quantities fixed for canned mushrooms and was therefore liable to a heavy fine.
The organizers of this survey found it interesting to pay sums of money to certain countries because they have no access to the sea and to grant a subsidy to apply for the granting of subsidies.
These ideas, however, did not originate in Brussels but in Prague.
"Not having a sea is a handicap.
We are going to ask the European Union for reimbursement.' So said the then Minister of Agriculture, Jaroslav Palas (ČSSD), in the autumn of 2004.
He argued that because of our wheat production and the so-called interventionist purchases, the State had been left with full stocks which it had then had to export.
According to Palas, the EU should have paid us millions of euros, because the Czech Republic is far from the ports.
The European Commission finally responded positively to the Czech request and called for tender for the purchase of wheat from landlocked countries.
The grants were offered to the municipalities by the Ministry of Local Development, headed by Minister Pavel Němec (US-DEU), and were to be used to draft applications for grants granted by Brussels.
The EU says: "odd rules are rare".
While regulations often provoke criticism in the Member States, many experts believe that the EU's efforts to regulate and improve the efficiency of the Union's functioning and its overall development are worthy of praise.
More serious, for example, according to the experts, is the problem of using EU subsidies for projects that have absolutely nothing to do with strengthening European integration, but which were imposed by the Member States during budget negotiations.
The fact that the Czech Republic, like other EU countries, has to fight in Brussels for the right to use specific names for these traditional products (a fight in which it does not always win) is causing strong emotions among the Czechs.
If after six years of battling the Germans and the Austrians, the Czechs successfully defended the name 'Olomoucké tvarůžky', for the 'Tuzemský rum' appellation which dates back to the 19th century, our producers had to replace it with the name 'Tuzemák'.
Only products based on cane sugar alcohol, not beet sugar, may bear the name 'rum'.
The official list of registered products in the EU today includes world-famous cheeses such as Feta or Gorgonzola, Lübeck mashup or Parma ham, Karlovy Vary biscuits ("Karlovarské suchary"), Pohořelice and Třeboň carps ("Pohořelický a Třeboňský kapr") and Žatec hops ("Žatecký chmel").
The Pardubice spice bread ('Pardubický perník') and the cakes called 'Cornets de Hořice' ('hořické trubičky') can also be proud of their Community trade marks.
