The architects of the firm MVRDV prove that real adventures are not just a matter of imagination.To be convinced, just look at Spijkenisse and the newly erected mountain of books - 2 photos
"I think this building is funny, it looks very futuristic, it's something interesting to see", says Lisette Verhaig, a passerby on the side of the street.
Stefan Spermon, a computer engineer at a large company nearby, tells us, "Yes, it's a really nice building".
But I wonder why we still need a library today.
Everybody has the Internet, an iPad and e-books.
No one goes willingly into one of those lousy libraries anymore, do they?
Spijkenisse, a sleepy town that has nothing to attract Rotterdam, holds a rather special record.
The municipality of 80,000 people has the lowest education rate in the Netherlands.
In order to give the brain a few extra neurons, the city decided a few years ago to contribute to the general culture by reproducing the seven fictional bridges on the euro banknotes in the form of pretty little painted concrete miniatures.
The cultural offensive was not successful.
The city authorities realized that there was only one way to get control of the statistics: to build a library!
Winy Maas, of the Rotterdam architects firm MVRDV, master of bold stick diagrams and creator of witty and often cynical buildings, accepted the project with his usual phlegm and entered the competition in 2003 with five books under his arm and a grin on his face.
And while the members of the jury still looked at each other, puzzled and shrugging their shoulders, Maas, the shameless one, piled his choice of books in order of size to make a pyramid, and ended his speech backed by activist arguments with a: "common thread!"
So here's my proposal for the Spijkenisse mountain of books, or as they say, the Boekenberg!
Nine years later, the $30 million mountain came out of the ground.
The building is part of a revitalization project that also includes an underground parking lot, a supermarket, a post office and some apartment buildings and community houses for a total of 50 homes.
In early November, the book mountain received the second prize "Best Library of NL 2012".
In addition, the project was selected for the Dutch National Wood Award 2012.
Thus this dull little town, which until now had nothing to offer but a postmodern pedestrian zone and a town hall of stunning ugliness, whose white facades invite the idea that they house a dairy, has been enriched with a contemporary architectural work.
Most importantly, Spijkenisse now has the first public cultural building in its history.
The Long Road to Reading
First impression: Eldorado from the book under the cheese bell.
While an elevator takes you to the heart of the massif, the real joys of reading and architecture are revealed to you when you step on the floor of the building and discover its topography.
The interior, made entirely of glass, is bright and clear, the Dutch brick floor and the elegant streetlights speak the language of the city's public squares.
The urban atmosphere is perfect.
We're already looking for public pews, dogs, and little boys and girls playing ball.
And everywhere books, books and books.
"Normally, the library racks are along the facade and in the middle is a large, dark room, which is often uncomfortable and impersonal", explains Willy Maas.
We completely upended the traditional spatial configuration and opened the reading spaces from the inside out.
The interior of the book mountain has been cleverly laid out: in the middle are the offices, the Internet library, the chess club, the environmental centre and the technical centre of the building.
The library's black bookcases are particularly beautiful, sometimes as canvases, sometimes as balustrades, sometimes as stairwells.
A new experience for sight, touch and smell.
Even hardened architects and engineers don't want unfamiliar materials.
"We wanted to work with recycled materials", explains Joop Trouborst, project manager at the municipality of Spijkenisse, in a reply to the Standard.
We found a waste product from agriculture in a Frisian farm.
In the Netherlands, synthetic membrane of one millimetre thickness has been used for many years as a substrate in greenhouses and fields.
It's cheap and it saves time.
The thin membrane is used for one or two seasons, and then it can be thrown away.
For the library, the membrane was compressed, for the first time in such quantities, into plates four centimetres thick.
Under the influence of heat and pressure, the Landbouwplastic (KPL) changes color and becomes a dark, homogeneous and resistant material, whose smell evokes both a new car and athletic shoes.
At the top of the 105 steps is the top of the mountain.
At the end of almost 500 meters, the literary café offers us a breathtaking view of the city, but also Dutch croquettes and ficus in pots.
These create an atmosphere, but they mainly contribute to maintaining the ideal level of humidity in the coastal mountain air.
Gifts for the New Soul
"It's amazing, but despite all the glass surfaces, this building is a model project in terms of ecology", says Trouborst.
The temperature of the building is controlled by geothermal.
Although the mountain of books is under a glass bell, the sun only shines for a short time inside, even on good days.
The thick wooden beams, set across from the glass façade, serve as a sunshade, intercepting much of the rays.
The atmosphere is very pleasant.
The fully automated blinds do the rest.
Stefan Spermon, the septic computer scientist mentioned earlier, has already ventured into the new library.
Lisette Verhaig was already there.
Cynthia Bogarde, a professor of traditional Chinese medicine, even describes the Boekenberg as the "soul finally found" of Spijkenisse.
A few weeks ago, at the inauguration, each citizen was invited to donate a book from his personal library.
This was done to fill the vacancies in the library, which was not yet fully filled (it now has 70,000 volumes).
The concept is a success.
The shelves are overflowing everywhere.
Architect Winy Maas said, "There is nothing worse than a half-empty library".
"I believe our invitation has created a certain relationship between every citizen and this new building.
Everyone knows that their book is part of this building.
Even if it's only for decoration".
This is how MVRDV reached the master discipline that is called, in professional jargon, "the creation of an identity".
Spijkenisse has written a new page in literary history.
Even if she may seem young and uneducated.
It is a new starting point for the birth of an identity.
Szabo: "Germans must play a greater role"
Germany abstained in the vote on the admission of the Palestinian state.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert on US-EU relations, this decision puts Berlin in a delicate political situation.
Deutsche Welle: Earlier this week, Germany announced its intention to vote against the Palestinian demand for observer status at the United Nations.
But then she chose to abstain.
Why would you do that?
Stephen Szabo: Germany doesn't approve of what the Israelis did to Gaza.
However, Berlin must be cautious, as it has a special relationship with Israel.
But I also think that she does not support the American position either.
Germany wanted to assert its independence, but without being too critical of Israel.
During the Libyan uprising in March 2011, Germany also abstained from voting on the establishment of a no-fly zone.
Finally, NATO imposed this measure.
Does Germany have difficulty in taking a clear position on major international issues?
The answer is yes.
The reason for this is that Berlin is reviewing its foreign policy, seeking to move away from a policy, so to speak, defined by the Americans and to establish a German foreign policy.
The situation is further complicated by the lack of a coherent and common policy within the Union.
The Germans are therefore facing off on several fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I think they're still groping for that role, but they're on the road to a more "normal" foreign policy.
A foreign policy, as in France or Britain
What does the term "normal" foreign policy mean to Germans?
It shows a willingness to adopt positions independent of those of the United States and the European partners, including on national issues.
I believe that German foreign policy is also determined by its economic policy, i.e. its exports and its relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China and the Middle East.
German economic interests are to some extent different from those of the other great powers: Germany must therefore protect its interests.
Did these economic interests influence Germany's position on the Middle East conflict and its abstention from voting at the United Nations?
Firstly, Germany has important opportunities in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf countries.
That is why Berlin must be careful not to offend public opinion, but also the elites of the Arab countries.
This is undoubtedly a decisive factor.
However, I would not attach too much importance to it, because it is not an exclusively one-sided relationship.
But this is a crucial element in German strategic thinking.
Does Germany damage its relations with the United States by abstaining in important votes, as in the case of Palestine?
I think that the Europeans and the Americans understand perfectly well the German position.
That is why I think the fracture is not as serious as it was in the case of the Libyan question.
Perhaps Germany will even be more respected.
Germany has thus demonstrated that it must be taken seriously as an international actor and that its interests must be taken into account.
In Europe, opinions on the Palestinian initiative are mixed.
The United States, on the other hand, has announced its clear veto.
Do the views differ between the United States and most European countries?
There have always been differences because of the domestic American political scene.
I think that the Obama administration is secretly showing a great understanding of the European position.
But given the political configuration of the country, the government cannot defend its position publicly.
I believe that the real differences of opinion are not so great as they always seem.
If you look at the relationship between Obama and Israeli Prime Minister Netanyahu, you will notice that Obama is far from overwhelmed with enthusiasm for Netanyahu's policies.
Does Germany have difficulty reconciling its close relations with Israel and the United States on the one hand with the position of the major European partners on the other?
I don't think it makes things any easier for the Germans.
Of course, it would be a little easier for the Germans if there were a coherent and uniform European policy, but that is not the case today.
They cannot therefore be part of a wider political line and must assert their singular position.
That is what they are doing now on the euro issue.
In my view, Germany will in future be a driving force and will push Europe to adopt a European position.
It's not easy for Germany, especially because of the relations with Israel.
This question has always been a sensitive one.
But I think the Germans are well aware that they must play a role which is more independent.
Does Germany see itself as a major player on the international stage, or does Germany only want to play a key role?
Or does she still have trouble taking on leading roles?
Germany is still not used to it, it is still uncomfortable with it and, for obvious reasons, it is still finding it difficult to play a more important role.
If we look at the euro crisis, for example, we see that every time Germany decides to weigh more, there is a lot of anti-German sentiment.
It doesn't make it easy for the Germans.
In fact, it's still the same problem: you don't want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
From this point of view, Germany is in a much more delicate position than the United States.
She has to deal with neighbors and a wide variety of opinions, and it is not easy.
Today, the influence of the United States on European politics is only diminishing, but at the moment the EU is not filling that void, so who is left?
The Germans will simply have to play a bigger role.
And even if they don't like it, even if it's unpleasant and they're only less appreciated, that's life!
Stephen Szabo is the Deputy Director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, D.C., an institute where academics and policy experts from Europe and North America collaborate on analysing the challenges facing the transatlantic community.
Szabo is also a fellow at the German Marshall Fund, where he specializes in German politics, U.S. foreign policy, and transatlantic relations.
"Brand protection" in China: when Puma and Armani suddenly become Chinese
Armani and Polo Ralph Lauren are brands known throughout the world.
Armani Polo... what is this really about?
Behind this name is a trademark officially registered in China, but which has nothing to do with the original company.
The trademark is thus protected in such a way that the company bearing the name cannot bring a complaint.
And even if she could, he's not sure she'd win the case.
"It is becoming increasingly difficult for foreigners to protect their trademarks in China", says Thomas Pattloch, a lawyer at Taylor Wessing who specialises in infringements of property rights in the Far East.
Every week, a new file comes to my desk.
The copycatters only need a few more letters to register their trademarks.
So instead of Gucci, we're going to record Lu-Gucci, and instead of Prada, we're going to record Prada-Kny.
German companies, such as sports equipment manufacturer Puma, are also being copied legally.
Pattloch opens a file containing the registrations made with the Beijing Trademark Office.
On September 14, 2010, a Chinese company registered the brand Zegna DF Puma, a name that the firm artificially created by appropriating part of the name of Ermenegildo Zegna, the fashion house.
It is a known fact that the Chinese have become the world champions of copying and intellectual property infringement.
In large cities, there are many storey-high malls that sell almost nothing but counterfeit goods.
However, the Pattloch case is different: his clients instruct him to address the fact that the Chinese Trademark Office officially grants Chinese companies the right to use a name that is already protected in another country.
The Chinese call it "Bang Mingpai", the parent brand.
The term is derived from "Bang Dakuan".
This is the term used for women who marry wealthy men.
The Chinese authorities say they have nothing to blame themselves for.
"It's bad for business, we have to fight this trend", Pattloch demands.
