The Zulu word "imbongi" means "story-teller" or "praise-singer".
No one in the area can fluently speak Bantu, but everyone can sing it.
For almost 10 years, the choir has been rehearsing songs in this foreign language that it brought to Germany and now returns to its home region: South Africa.
For the village of Esitjeni, which is 8,733 kilometres by air from Heidelberg in the north-western Kingdom of Swaziland, is dependent on the vocal power of the German choir.
40% of people affected
The village has about 2,000 inhabitants, some living in modest huts of straw or dirt and the majority of them are children.
More than 300 of them are orphans, as their parents have died of HIV.
In Esitjeni, one can see on a smaller scale the ills that afflict Swaziland: the highest HIV infection rate and the lowest life expectancy in the world, according to UNICEF.
The population almost never accepts male circumcision, a measure that nevertheless guarantees a proven reduction in the risk of infection by half.
More than 40% of the population of Swaziland is infected with the immunodeficiency virus and it is not uncommon for people to die in their mid-30s.
During a group trip to Africa in the spring of 2005, the choir had the opportunity to discover the village, and the Imbongis saw many children on the streets who not only lack parental care, but also simply everything: food, clothing, education.
In a poor country, without a school diploma, there is simply no prospect.
At first, it was just a few people who personally committed themselves to paying a few dollars a year so that they could send a child to school and provide a hot meal every day.
