Facts about sexually transmitted infections
What are the most common sexually transmitted diseases?
Bacterial STIs include syphilis, chlamydia, and gonorrhea.
The most common STDs are HIV, human papillomavirus, genital herpes, or hepatitis.
Pubis lice and scabies are parasitic STDs.
Which groups are mainly affected?
Syphilis and gonorrhea are common in men who have sex with other men.
The Robert Koch Institute estimates that at least four out of five reported cases of syphilis in Germany are caused by male sexual contact.
In heterosexual adults, chlamydia-related infections, trichomoniasis, candidiasis (fungal), gonorrhoea and human papillomavirus are common sexually transmitted diseases.
The rate of HIV transmission among heterosexual adults is relatively low in Germany, but about 20% of new HIV infections are observed among this group.
The rate of chlamydia-related infections is significantly higher among young people than among other population groups.
According to European statistics, three quarters of all infections are among young people aged 15 to 25.
In addition, in Germany, the human papilloma virus is common among young people.
What is the evolution of infection?
It is not compulsory to report all sexually transmitted diseases.
According to the Robert Koch Institute, the number of syphilis cases more than doubled in 10 years, from 1,967 in 2001 to 3,698 in 2011.
Since 2007, the number of new HIV infections has been decreasing.
In 2011, there were about 2,700 cases.
This represents a decrease of one tenth compared to the previous year.
What are the symptoms of a sexually transmitted disease?
Infectious diseases can cause genital abscesses, urinary pain, discharge, lower abdominal pain, and the appearance of pimples and warts.
However, they usually do not cause pain or other symptoms and so remain hidden.
How can you protect yourself?
Condoms can reduce the risk of infection, but they do not provide 100% protection.
The reason is that pathogens of sexually transmitted diseases can also be transmitted by lubricating infection or close bodily contact.
So experts recommend that anyone who frequently changes sex partners undergo regular physical examinations.
Most STI diagnosed early can be cured and late-stage complications can be prevented.
