Is Norway rakfisk the most smelly fish in the world?
The five million people who live in Norway enjoy one of the highest living standards not only in Europe but also in the world.
Could the secret of the country's success be tied to the locals' appetite for a fish that smells extremely good?
Have some of those advanced cheeses.
Put them in the middle of a pile of wet, dirty football clothes.
Wait a week.
And you get the unpleasant smell of rakfisk, one of Norway's most popular dishes.
I'm in the small town of Fagernes, about three hours from Oslo.
It snows, the scenery is spectacular - and that pervasive smell permeates the air.
Rakfisk is made up of trout sprinkled with salt and fermented in water for a period of time - depending on the smell you want it to exhale - which can be up to a year.
When it gets dark and it gets cold, Norwegians gather en masse to attend a festival held here in Fagernes, dedicated to this incredible culinary specialty.
"You eat raw and then you swallow a glass of aquavit", explains full-time local firefighter Havard Halvarsen, also known as "Rakfisk General", who is responsible for the festival management.
All around us, people are swallowing little pieces of fish and stuffing themselves with a lot of booze.
"Some people prefer aquavit to rakfisk", says Havard.
The drink kills the smell.
I'm trying out a few pieces.
If you can avoid passing it under your nose, it's not bad - it reminds you of sushi that would have spent long hours on a bus.
Rakfisk dates back to a time when Norway was poor, before refrigeration was invented, the fish was dipped in airtight water barrels, then salted in the fall.
Then, during the winter, after the fish had been well fermented, it was taken out and - no doubt with the senses dulled by alcohol - eaten.
In the previous generation, thousands of Norwegians were forced to leave their country in search of work, mainly emigrating to the United States.
Now, the population is growing rapidly - over 13% are immigrants, attracted by full employment, high wages and a comprehensive health system.
Sweden, their old rival, whose country was not so long ago richer than Norway, crossed the border to come to work.
Rakfisk is considered something important, a vital, though fragrant, element of Norway's past.
It's one of the most expensive dishes.
But everything is expensive - a pint of beer or a sandwich will cost you 10 euros each.
Norway is not often mentioned in the international news, which is not to its disadvantage.
Here people are not willing to talk about Anders Breivik, the right-wing racist who shot 77 people, including women and children.
When they refer to this killing, they refer to the "July 22 incident".
The Norwegians find it hard to accept that in their peaceful country, one of their own could commit such a barbaric act.
Since the early 1970s, Norway has been rich from its oil and gas industry, one of the largest in the world.
"But oil is not the only reason for our success", explains our waiter Anna, with blond hair and piercing blue eyes, the image of Nordic well-being, holding a tray of rakfisk in her hand.
We are - how you say - a cautious people.
His English, like that of most people who live here, is perfect.
We're discreet, we don't like to be seen.
Norway has managed its oil wealth with great caution - all but a small percentage of the money from this industry is invested in a special fund for the benefit of future generations.
When other countries were throwing money out the window, in the years leading up to the international financial crisis, Norway kept its purse strings very tight.
"As long as we can ski in the winter and hike in the summer, we are happy", says Anna.
"Not to mention the rakfisk", she adds with a carefree laugh.
I'm standing under the snow and I'm standing in line to buy food - I've had my dose of rakfisk.
On the menu, a hamburger made of eel, a real discovery, it's excellent.
But tonight, the smell of fish is everywhere.
The hotel I'm staying at is one of many places where rakfisk is served for dinner and where you can vote for the best of them - or maybe the most smelly of them.
There's a TV show where the host wears a bow tie, surrounded by rakfisk plates.
It's like the Eurovision song contest.
"What did you give the best fish in the Thor-Juergen Mountains?"
"Here are our points, Harvard".
We hear laughter and applause.
A man falls from his chair, possibly from over-watering.
Or maybe it's because of the fish fumes.
Mexico's Enrique Pena Nieto has had a rough start.
