Bradley Manning has not complained of ill-treatment, prosecutors say.
Prosecutors are trying to counter claims of mistreatment that Bradley Manning was subjected to during detention.
The trial is about Manning's detention in a military prison in Quantico, Virginia.
The defense is requesting that the case be closed on the grounds that Manning's abduction was carried out under extremely difficult circumstances.
The soldier is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents.
Prosecutors tried to show on Friday that Private Bradley Manning -- accused of being behind the biggest leak of classified information in the history of the U.S. military -- missed numerous opportunities to complain about the mistreatment he claims he suffered while in military custody.
In cross-examination with Manning during a preliminary hearing at Ft. Meade, Maryland, Attorney Major Ashden Fein claimed that weekly visits to Manning by officers during his nine months of detention in Quantico, Virginia, revealed no complaints about his treatment.
The cross-examination -- during a hearing, the defense filed a motion demanding that the Manning case be dismissed on the grounds that the detention was made under very difficult conditions and constituted a sufficiently severe punishment -- took place a day after Manning testified that he had contemplated suicide while in custody.
This military intelligence analyst, arrested in June 2010, is accused of stealing thousands of classified documents while serving in Iraq.
The documents were then published online by WikiLeaks.
WikiLeaks never confirmed that Manning was their source.
At Friday's hearing, Fein reviewed with Manning the forms that officers filled out after their meeting with Manning, while he was held at the military prison in Quantico, where he was subjected to maximum custodial isolation from July 2010 to April 2011.
The officers asked Manning questions and wrote down his answers.
When Fein discussed the forms on Friday, Manning acknowledged that the treatment he received from his guards was "excellent" and that the treatment he received in the prison was overall "very professional".
The forms do not report any complaints of ill-treatment, although the officers directly questioned him about his prison treatment, Fein said.
Manning replied that he had verbally expressed concerns about certain issues and that the visiting officers had discussed his concerns and indicated that they would address them, but they did not record the issues raised.
"They wrote 'no problem' (after addressing the concerns), and that didn't mean I didn't raise problems", Manning said.
Military Judge Col. Denise Lind also asked Manning why he had not complained about his treatment during a January 2011 interview with the special committee that had met to discuss the suicidal thoughts he had expressed in writing a few months earlier.
Manning responded that his intention during the meeting was to have his restrictive status changed to indicate a "risk of injury".
The military said they had assigned him this restrictive status -- a level below close surveillance for suicide risk -- for his own protection and the safety of others.
"I wanted the staff to know that I was fine, and I wanted to be removed from that status... to have a better quality of life from my perspective", Manning said.
Manning testified Thursday about his arrest in Iraq and his transfer to Kuwait, where he was held for nearly two months before being transferred to the military prison at the Marine Corps base in Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He said he contemplated suicide when he was in Kuwait and once fainted in the heat.
He added that not being kept informed of what was going to happen to him or what was happening in the rest of the world was very distressing.
"My world was reduced to Camp Arafjon, to this cage", Manning said Thursday.
I thought I was gonna die in that cage.
Once in Quantico, Manning said he spent most of his time in a small cell -- at least 21 hours and sometimes more than 23 hours -- without company.
Manning also said that the only items he had were a mattress, a blanket, flip-flops, clothes and his glasses.
He tried to keep moving, because sleeping or lying down during the day was against the rules.
Manning also said that when he tried to sleep, he had a light in his eyes, lit outside his cell.
If the guards couldn't see his face when he turned around at night, they would wake him up so they could see his face.
Manning's lawyer filed a formal complaint for Manning's treatment in January 2011.
Manning was placed in a military prison at Fort Leavenworth, Kansas, in April 2011.
Also on Friday, the judge questioned Manning about an allegation reported in his testimony Thursday -- that after he was forced to sleep naked all night in his cell in Quantico, he was forced to stand naked in front of guards and other inmates one morning during the appeal.
Manning testified that at no point was he allowed to cover himself with a blanket during the call.
During Friday's questions from the judge, Manning said he had deduced from his guard's order that he had to drop his blanket that could have concealed his nakedness, but he acknowledged that no one had ordered him to drop it.
Manning testified Thursday that he was forced to sleep naked the night before because he was trying to prove to an officer that he was not a danger to himself.
Manning reportedly told the officer that he could have used his underwear band or his thongs to injure himself, but he didn't.
That night, Manning testified that his underwear, flip-flops, and glasses had been removed from his cell.
His lawyers hope that at least the judge will take into account his experiences in detention and significantly reduce his sentence if he is found guilty by a military court, a trial that is scheduled for early next year.
The defense said Manning plans to plead guilty to the lesser charges and fight for the dismissal of other charges deemed too extreme.
The hearing is expected to resume this weekend, with prosecutors expected to argue that the conditions of detention were justified.
The Pentagon has confirmed that Manning was incarcerated in accordance with the regulations that govern the conditions of detention of all inmates at Quantico.
The charges against Manning include theft of public property or documents, colluding with the enemy, resulting in the illegal publication of information on the Internet, and transmitting information relating to national defense.
If all the charges are dropped, he faces life in prison.
