Old feuds, new Middle East
The cease-fire between Israel and Hamas is still a failure for peace.
Can there ever be a lasting peace between the Arabs and the Jews in the Middle East?
Another bloodshed seems to indicate that such a hope is futile.
While the same futile arguments persist as to who started it, dozens of buildings have been razed to the ground; more than 140 Palestinians, most of them civilians, and six Israelis have been killed; and, for the first time, rockets from Gaza have landed near Tel Aviv, Israel's capital, and the holy city of Jerusalem.
But while Israelis and Palestinians seem to be stuck in their old conflict, all around them, the Middle East is changing.
The Arab Spring blew it all to pieces, and whether we like it or not, Palestinians and Israelis are caught up in this regional upheaval.
