The laws for neutral cigarette packets have come into force in Australia
Warnings and pictures of diseased organs cover the dark green packages which are all identical, regardless of brand
This legislation, which has been enacted in Australia, is a world first, with the logos and colors being replaced by dark olive green and horrible photos of diseased organs and images of children and babies whose diseases were caused by the smoking of their parents.
Apart from the different pictures and health warnings, the only difference between the packages, since Saturday, is the brand name, printed in small letters on all the packages.
This is the strictest tobacco packaging regime in the world.
The Australian federal government stated that the goal was to discourage young people from smoking by removing all glamorous depictions.
Studies have shown that if people don't start smoking before the age of 26, there's a 99 percent chance they'll never start.
"Even at a very young age, children understand the message conveyed by tobacco manufacturers through their brand image", said Federal Minister of Health Tanya Plibersek, citing studies that have found, for example, that children associate the crown of a logo with a princess".
Even though Australia has the lowest smoking rate in the world and these changes have little impact on the profits of multinational companies, other countries are considering similar approaches.
The tobacco industry lobbied against the bill.
Tobacco manufacturers said this would revive the black market trade, which would make it easier to access cheaper cigarettes.
"There will be harmful consequences from this legislation", said Scott McIntyre of British American Tobacco Australia.
Counterfeiters in China and Indonesia will sell many more counterfeit cigarettes on the streets of Australia.
Others said that this law had given their activity a boost.
Sandra Ha of Zico Import Pty Ltd, a small family-owned business, said that the demand for cigarette cases, including silicone to hide the horrible packaging, has increased sharply two months ago since British American Tobacco, Britain's Imperial Tobacco, Philip Morris and Japan Tobacco challenged the law and lost in the High Court of Australia.
Ha said Zico sold 6,000 to wholesalers and is waiting for replenishment.
We're doing well.
The only downside, experts say, is the popularity of social media and the targeted population.
After a series of Australian laws banning TV advertising, sports sponsorship and requiring retailers to conceal cigarettes, tobacco marketing is now available online.
Australia has banned advertising on the Web by local businesses and websites, but it cannot prevent foreign websites from doing so.
"If you're in the tobacco business and you have a small display window to promote your products, the Internet is the place to go", said Becky Freeman, a public health researcher at the University of Sydney.
Freeman noticed an increase in contributions from some ordinary citizens in favor of brands on social media such as YouTube, Twitter and Facebook.
We have to ask ourselves if this is a simple Marlboro cigarette-loving citizen who has taken the trouble to make a video, or is this a marketing campaign orchestrated by an agency?
British American Tobacco Australia said the industry is focusing on the new regulation rather than marketing.
