After reviewing many publications and presenting the idea to a panel of about 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues defined boredom as an experience of "wanting to do something but failing to engage in a satisfying activity".
What differentiates boredom from apathy, he says, is that the person is not actually undertaking a task even though they would like to.
With apathy, he says, there's no desire to do anything.
At the heart of boredom, he said, is "the interruption of the attention process, coupled with a sullen mood and the feeling that time is passing slowly".
Boredom can strongly resemble depression.
But Professor Eastwood said that while the two may be linked, bored people tend to think the problem is the environment or the world, while depressed people think the problem is them.
Sometimes we think we're bored when it's really a concentration problem.
In their study, "The Unengaged Mind: Defining Boredom in Terms of Attention", which was published in the journal Perspectives on Psychological Science in September, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues highlighted an earlier experiment in which participants listened to a tape of the voice of a person reading a magazine article.
Some groups heard the sound of a TV show that had no connection at all coming from the next room, others heard the TV show only, and a third group heard no sound at all.
Those who heard the TV at a low volume said they were more bored than the other two groups - they had trouble concentrating, but didn't know why, and attributed this concentration problem to boredom.
When you're trying to focus on a difficult or demanding task, a disruption in attention can lead to boredom, said Mark J. Fenske, an associate professor of neuroscience at the University of Guelph in Ontario and one of the authors of the study.
On the other hand, when you are doing a boring task, "like looking at objects on a production line, music can help you not get bored".
In fact, he says, we now know that when you squirm or scratch, these gestures, often considered signs of boredom, are actually a good way to stay physically more alert.
"Studies have shown that children who are allowed to giggle learn more and retain more information than those who are forced to sit still", said Professor Fenske.
We all get bored at one time or another - my flight delay, a speaker with a monochord voice, a particularly boring movie.
But some people are more prone to boredom than others.
To measure this, researchers developed a "Boring Predisposition Scale" in the 1980s.
The scale includes statements such as, "Many of the tasks I perform are repetitive and monotonous", and "I have so many interests that I don't have time to do them all".
Using such a scale, researchers found that boys tend to be bored more often than girls, said Stephen Vodanovich, a professor of psychology at the University of West Florida, and one of the things they need is a wide variety of stimulating activities.
But teenagers are usually quick to get carried away.
In 1991, Reed Larson, a professor of personal and community development at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment in which he reached out to nearly 400 teenagers and their parents seven to eight times a day via a beeper.
It found that 32 percent of the teenagers reported being bored at school and during their homework, while 23 percent reported being bored when they were not at school.
In contrast, 3 percent of parents said they were bored.
Professor Larson said he did not know whether the boredom rates of today, 21 years from now, would be higher or lower.
But he added that he knew that "adolescence is a time when boredom reaches its peak", partly because children and adolescents have little control over what they want to do.
Let me ask you again, is boredom good for you?
Sometimes it doesn't, because in its extreme form, it can lead people to take absurd physical risks, gamble, or abuse certain substances to pass the time, as studies show.
On the other hand, many philosophers and writers suggest a link between boredom and creativity, said Professor Vodanovich, who has studied the problem for more than two decades.
"Boring is the brain's way of letting you know you should be doing something else", said Gary Marcus, a professor of psychology at N.Y.U.
But the brain doesn't always know what the most appropriate thing to do is.
If you get bored and use that energy to play guitar and cook, it will make you happy.
But if you watch TV, it will make you happy in the short term, but not in the long term.
So if your child is bored and you give him an iPad, he won't be bored, but he won't have learned to take care of himself or to self-regulate, says Dr. Fenske.
And "this self-regulation goes from one situation to another", he says.
Your child is not just learning to have fun, he is gaining more self-control in other areas.
I don't think we should glorify boredom.
Just like I don't think we should be criticizing him.
To feel comfortable outside the constant seething of activities and technology is the goal we should strive towards.
Professor Eastwood agrees with that.
"We need to be bored more often, but boredom awakens a keen and frenetic desire to be connected to something meaningful", he said.
He says what people are looking for is a way to unplug and enjoy the downtime.
"In an environment where we are constantly hyperstimulated", he added, "it is difficult to find ways of getting into something when the noise stops".
In Colorado, no guidelines for the new marijuana law
Nineteen-year-old college student and football player Anthony Orozco in Colorado is charged with something that will soon become legal in his state: possession of marijuana and a pipe used to smoke it.
