"We are treated like criminals", said Mr. Orozco.
But is he?
In the weeks of uncertainty that followed Colorado's vote to legalize the use of small amounts of marijuana for personal use, the response to hundreds of cases involving low-level drug use was more about location than law.
Here and in Washington state, which has passed a similar measure, hundreds of marijuana-related crimes have been dismissed.
Police departments have stopped charging adults 21 and older for minor marijuana possession, as the law goes into effect in the coming weeks.
But prosecutors in Colorado's more conservative districts have called for accelerating existing marijuana cases and continue to charge people with possession.
In parallel, several cities from the suburbs of Denver to the mountains of the West are currently voting to prevent the opening of state-licensed marijuana retail stores in their neighborhoods.
"Things are moving so fast that I don't know what the future holds", said Daniel J. Oates, the chief of police in Aurora, east of Denver.
The regulatory agencies in Washington state are also asking a lot of questions.
They are seeking guidance on how to install a licensing system, allowing production, manufacture, distribution and sale - before the December 1, 2013 deadline.
They say that Colorado, whether you like it or not, is ahead of most states in regulating marijuana, first for therapeutic use and now for personal use.
"Colorado has a more regulated market, and that's a good indicator", said Brian E. Smith, spokesman for the Washington State Liquor Control Board.
But no place or system, Mr. Smith admits, can do more than suggest what works.
"There is no real precedent on which we could base ourselves", he said.
Washington's law, called I-502, takes effect on December 6, leaving a legal vacuum of a year, during which the permit system will still not exist, while marijuana possession will be legal.
Meanwhile, practical questions remain: how to balance the state's mandate that guarantees appropriate access to licensed marijuana and prohibits the establishment of cannabis retail establishments within a 30-mile radius of a school, park, playground or daycare.
"There will be no place more difficult than urban areas to set up a licensed cannabis business, especially in the Seattle metro area", said Ben Livingston, a spokesman for the Center for Cannabis Legalization, a newly formed research group.
On November 21, Aurora Police Chief Oates sent an email to his officers announcing that the City Attorney would no longer prosecute people 21 and older for possessing small amounts of marijuana, and that the police should stop charging people for this type of offense "with immediate effect".
Chief Oates said that the police will enforce the new court rulings that regulate the activity of those who grow marijuana for medical purposes, and that he will continue to prosecute drug traffickers and dealers.
In Weld County, northern Colorado, district attorney Ken Buck embodies a more rigid view.
After the vote, he said his office would continue to deal with marijuana possession cases, mainly to pressure users to get clean.
At present, 119 people are charged with possession of 56 grams or less of marijuana, but many of them are facing other charges.
"Our office has an obligation to prosecute those persons who committed a crime which, at the time of the facts, was a recognised offence", said Mr Buck.
Reactions have been complicated even in rural areas like Mesa County, where voters have rejected the initiative in favor of restricted marijuana use.
Police in Grand Junction, the largest city in the county, are no longer serving adults for possession of narcotics.
County prosecutor Pete Hautzinger supported the decision, but also decided not to dismiss all marijuana possession cases without a trial.
"I don't feel like I'm wasting my time by continuing to enforce the law until it changes", he said.
Although 55 percent of Colorado voters supported the measure, providing a proper legal and governmental framework for personal marijuana use is not an easy task.
And the mixed reactions that have been observed in different American cities highlight the deep ambivalence among local officials regarding the legalization of marijuana.
"It's a cultural barrier" with prosecutors, said Sean McAllister, a Denver lawyer representing people accused of marijuana use and a local spokesman for the National Organization for the Reform of Marijuana Laws.
"They have spent a good part of their lives prosecuting people who used marijuana, so they have a hard time accepting that it is legal", he said.
As the first states to treat the moderate use of marijuana on the same level as alcohol, Colorado and Washington state are on their way to becoming a case law for drug legalization.
As advocates and state representatives anticipate a new frontier of legalized sales, they anxiously await guidance from the federal government, which still views the sale and cultivation of marijuana as federal crimes.
Marijuana legalization advocates hope the Justice Department will back down.
Despite some well-publicized arrests of medical marijuana patients and sellers, the federal government has mostly allowed businesses selling medical marijuana to operate in Colorado, Washington, and 16 other states.
While police are unlikely to break into homes to seize small bags of drugs, they are likely to oppose the licensed marijuana businesses that are allowed to sell marijuana for personal use under the new laws, said Kevin A. Sabet, a former policy adviser to the Obama administration.
Many Colorado cities didn't wait for the federal authorities to act.
Long before the votes, some local governments approved moratoriums on the creation of new marijuana retail stores, even if it's only a one-year delay.
Last week, the city of Montrose got a six-month moratorium, and they're expected to impose that ban next week.
"We don't want to be in a situation where a permit is granted to someone and then we have a federal problem", said city councilman Bob Nicholson.
Our community voted against this amendment.
We're interested in the community vote rather than the state vote.
