The hardest job in the world: Kawah Ijen human mules
For four dollars, Indonesian volcano porters risk their lives and health by carrying 70 kilos of sulfur over the steep stone paths.
There are people who work in hell and others who work in literal hell.
One such person is Antwo Wijaya, one of 400 miners who earn their living by carrying sulfur from the Kawah Ijen volcano on the Indonesian island of East Java.
He has to work every day to the bottom of the crater, where sulfuric gas from the bowels of the earth solidifies in contact with air.
After collecting large rocks of sulphur, weighing a total of about 70 kilograms, he places them in two bamboo baskets and carries them on his shoulders across the steep paths.
It is only 250 meters to the summit of the 2,386-meter-high volcano, but the exhausted bearers take more than 40 minutes to climb this distance at the pace of a tortoise, keeping their balance and measuring their steps so as not to trip and fall into the precipice.
They know that a misstep could cost them their lives, as happened to a French tourist who fell to her death from the Kawah Ijen volcano several years ago.
The miners at Kawah Ijen earn 5 cents for every kilo of sulfur extracted.
Once on the top, they fight their way through the tourists who photograph them as if they were circus animals, and carrying the heavy baskets, they walk the three kilometers to the scales that a mining company has installed a little below at 1,850 meters.
The company that has been operating the volcano since 1960, PT Candi Ngrimbi, and its employees, are paid 662 Indonesian Rupees (US$1.45) per kilo of sulphur.
She then sells it for 10,000 rupees (83 cents) to the petrochemical industry, since this mineral is very present in everyday life and is used to make candles, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even used to bleach sugar.
"Because we carry about 70 kilos, we earn about 46,000 rupees ($3.70) for each trip", explains Anto, who usually makes three trips a day.
Each one takes him 3 hours and he finishes exhausted, but this earns him 138,000 rupees (US$80) at the end of the day.
Although it may seem a pittance for such superhuman effort, it is three times what he would earn in the fields.
"The income of the miners is very high here, where the coffee harvest is paid 15,000 rupees ($1.50) a day and the average monthly salary is two million rupees ($1.70)", says the porter who once worked as a bricklayer on the tourist island of Bali.
There, his salary was 75,000 rupees (6.20 euros) a day and the work was not so hard, but Anto returned to his family in Banyuwangi, a village near the volcano, for a reason that, in Indonesia, is as indisputable as sulfur: "I married a young girl from Bali, where they are Hindu, and brought her back to Java to convert to Islam".
Anto has asthma, breathing difficulties, constant coughing, and eyes irritated by toxic gases.
At 27, he's spent three of his life defying danger on the Kawah ljen, but the sulfur has already started to take its toll on him despite covering his face with a mask and wearing special gloves.
Anto suffers from asthma, breathing difficulties, constant coughing, and his eyes are irritated by the toxic gases emitted by the volcano.
That's the price he has to pay for pursuing his dream.
"I'm going to work for two more years, because I want to open a shop or study Spanish or French", he promises in a more than acceptable English.
Abused by life, this friendly and intelligent young man could be a tour guide, a waiter, or a hotel receptionist, but instead he is doing the job of a mule.
It shares an unhealthy wooden hut with other carriers, rising every day at two in the morning because sulfur keeps gushing out at night, when its characteristic yellow color turns blue and glows in the darkness.
Defying the darkness, Anto descends into the crater by illuminating himself with a small lamp attached to his helmet, which he bought himself with his own money.
Some 400 porters carry the baskets of sulphur on their shoulders from the bottom of the crater.
Despite its comfortable profits, the mining company has not mechanized the extraction of sulfur to save costs and does not provide any equipment to porters who work on their own account and are paid by weight.
They also do not pay the 30,000 rupees ($1.75) surcharge per camera, in addition to the entrance fee of 15,000 rupees ($1.85) that the park guards charge tourists who come to photograph the volcano and its human mules.
"This job is for the animals, not for the humans", protests Madrusin, a 42-year-old, stout porter who has worked at Kawah Ijen for thirty years, since he left college.
Capable of carrying up to 110 kilos, he says he will not stop working "as long as he can", because he needs money to raise his 3 sons, aged between 10 and 18.
I'm not going to retire, I'm going to die here because the volcano is my whole life.
Although the sulfur damages the throat and irritates the eyes when the wind turns and traps the miners in the thick columns of smoke that come out of the volcano, they are so hardened that no one complains of suffering from serious illnesses - to which are added, of course, their usual respiratory problems, arthrosis, pain in the knees and shoulders, deformed by the weight of the baskets.
By balancing the basket on his back, Unainik, 53, can only carry 50 kilos.
Each day, he and his companions extract 15 tons of sulfur from the volcano, which is transported by three trucks to the Tamansari warehouse, 18 kilometers away along a goat trail covered with weeds.
"I will not retire, I will die here because the volcano is my whole life", Unainik says, opening her mouth wide, revealing several missing teeth.
The eldest of his five children, aged 30, also works as a sulphur porter.
Time passes, but misery is passed on from generation to generation. One of the most difficult jobs in the world is the work of the human mules of the volcano Kawah Ijen.
