The last time it was above 2 as the renewal rate was in 1976.
So why don't Singaporeans have more children?
Tan Ming Wei, director of marriage and family policy at the National Population Division, says it is due to "better education" and "a wider choice of career opportunities".
"This has given people a wider range of options in terms of life goals and priorities, beyond marriage and starting a family", she explains.
These changes in social norms have contributed to the rise in the number of single people and to the delay in marriage and childbearing, resulting in a decrease in the birth rate in Singapore.
Meanwhile, an immigration policy aimed at radically increasing immigration to counter the declining population has created resentment among the local population.
In Singapore, there are websites that are rife with thinly disguised xenophobia against new immigrants, especially Chinese who are accused of pulling down salaries and not fitting in.
The increase in immigration is also seen as one of the reasons why the ruling party in Singapore last year had its worst election results since independence.
Since the elections, they have tried to correct the problem by introducing quotas and higher taxes for foreign workers.
Unexpected consequences
While the falling birth rate has known effects on a country's economic growth, tax revenues, health costs and immigration policies, the Singapore example also has unintended consequences.
The government is trying to avoid the construction of many small houses.
For example, it started to affect the real estate industry.
The urban development authorities have begun to control the number of small apartments, known as "shoe boxes", that can be built in certain areas of the city.
These apartments have a surface of 46 square metres and are very successful in sales.
However, authorities are concerned that they may promote a celibate lifestyle and discourage developers who wish to build large single-family homes.
But Lim Yew Soon, managing director of the real estate company EL Developers, says that his "shoe boxes" are selling much faster than larger homes.
They are more popular, in the sense that these dwellings are built much faster than larger ones.
For that reason, it's much more profitable for our treasury.
However, he admits that the new standards give clearer instructions to developers, who were previously put in a bind if they wanted to offer too small housing in a project.
Too much stress
Singapore is a city-state.
While these new regulations may be a step towards increasing the national birth rate, by talking to Singaporeans who work in the financial district downtown, it does not seem to have much effect.
"People are under a lot of stress, houses are expensive, education is expensive, so people put it off", says one young executive.
Other people can have children.
"But I think it's important to have my money and my time", says another young man in his 20's.
Both men and women cite career stress and the cost of access to property and education as reasons for not having children.
So while the government is trying to convince its citizens to have children, when it comes to making babies, Singaporeans themselves have the final say.
What 's private offline is private online .
Confidentiality
According to the Royal Spanish Academy Dictionary, it is the quality of private property or "the private property that we can protect from intrusion".
What is the private domain for those under 16?
How can we apply this definition in our daily life and on social networks?
Does he understand the dangers he is exposing himself to by posting on the Internet events that he would certainly not share offline?
The newspaper elPeriódico interviewed five young boys, aged between 10 and 15, who frequently use the Internet.
In four cases, they combined the term 'something very personal' on a personal level with 'password and username' when applying it to social networks.
"I won't reveal my most personal secrets in a post", says Jorge, 10, as he tries to explain the meaning of the term "private" on sites like Facebook, Twitter, Hotmail and Windows Live Messenger, where he has an account for two years.
"These are very secret things, my mother may know them but not everyone", he says.
I post funny pictures or games on my Facebook page.
I also talk to my friends.
"I won't share any of my pictures or anyone who would make a fool of himself", he said.
The boy recognizes that it is wrong to post obscene, naked pictures of people, crimes or humiliating or violent comments.
Jorge says he knows his 35 friends on Facebook and his nine Twitter followers.
Most of them are family.
His mother's on the list, she knows the password to one of the accounts.
I've started a Twitter account to express myself and write interesting tweets.
"I don't know if they reply, I just post them", he adds.
"Social networks are fun, I can talk to distant relatives or friends, in a quick way", he says.
He says he would never accept a proposal from a stranger.
He will not trust anyone who recommends a stranger.
The case of 14-year-old José is different.
The teenager has accounts on Hotmail, Facebook, My Space and Ask, on the latter, he admits not to know 20 of the people on his friends list.
"It doesn't worry me because we have something in common, like music", he says.
According to the boy, no one made advances or asked for his address or telephone number.
"If they pressured me or demanded it, I would simply delete them from my account", he admits.
José subscribed to Ask after reading a recommendation on Twitter.
The experiences we now know as cyberbullying are not new to the young boy.
A friend of mine's family was being blackmailed on a social network.
They threatened him and demanded money.
"He never knew who it was", he says.
According to José, the victim didn't close his account.
"He just passed it in private profile".
He then explains a series of manipulations to configure his account in a secure manner.
Unlike Jorge, this youngster would post photos of people he knows in awkward or embarrassing situations.
Yeah, I would if I was angry or pissed off.
"Even though I know it's cyberstalking", he says.
Key issues
Marielos Porras, an English professor and a graduate in Education and Learning, believes that in order to guide children and adolescents, we must understand that the purpose of social networks is to inform.
"The Internet was born as a way of finding information, but with the advent of these sites, the rules of the game have changed", she says.
Porras points out that academic Marc Prensky, who holds a master's degree in education from Yale University and is the author of the book "Digital Natives and Immigrants", uses these terms to explain the phenomenon.
Digital natives are those children and young people who were born with technology.
"We are the digital immigrants who have to teach them, while we are learning ourselves", she said.
He adds that the issue is complex, "because we ask them to have a defined standard on what is appropriate or not to disclose, publish or say at an age when they are not mature enough to do so".
"We also ask them to be selective when what matters most to them is to be popular, to have thousands of friends without thinking about the consequences", she adds.
The expert says that the most effective way to teach children and teenagers confidentiality is to use thought-provoking questions.
"Telling them not to do it is pointless", she says.
Next, Porras lists some examples: there are things you wouldn't tell a stranger, why do you do it on the Internet?
Or would you like it if they posted a picture of you like a friend's picture you posted?
Do you know what other people are posting about you?
When you identify party photos, do you ask other people's permission to identify them?
And also, does everyone need to know what you're doing every second?
Another point is to make them understand that they have to act online as they do offline.
It's the same rules.
"Outside the internet, everyone should act with respect, morality and other principles, and the same should be true on social networks", she says.
The monitoring
Eduardo Guardia, a university professor, a primary school teacher, and an educational consultant, says that it is vital that parents carefully read the terms and conditions of social networking sites.
Understanding each term will provide a solid foundation for discussing the implications of Internet accounts with your children.
"For example, age and what is allowed to share or publish", he said.
Guardia says that it is essential to remind children not to talk to strangers.
The UNASUR summit ended without the Lima Declaration being made public
The 6th Presidential Summit of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) ended today in Peru without the Lima Declaration being made public, although it was announced earlier and theoretically adopted by the 7 mandatees present.
Efe tried several times to access the document signed at the 6th Ordinary Meeting of Heads of State and Government of Unasur, but the Ministry of Foreign Affairs and the Presidency initially reported that it would be released after the summit, and then stated that it would be published at any moment on the Peruvian government's website.
When questioned about the text, they reported that its contents had been exposed by the President of Peru, Ollante Humala, during brief statements to the press.
Access to information on the summit was constantly restricted.
During the day, only the video without sound of the presidential assembly with the message "private session, audio restricted" was broadcast in the press room.
The few information that was circulated among journalists was that given by the press officers of some of the governments of UNASUR who were present at the meeting, with the exception of the Peruvian spokesman.
The only document leaked during the day was the list of presidents present, which caused some unease among the hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who demanded more important information.
Later, the Peruvian presidency sent an email to the media with the summit's "final declaration", but it was President Humala's speech and not the official document that concluded the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the 3rd Summit of the South American Arab Countries (ASPA) and, on this occasion, despite press pressures, it did not release the declaration also known as the Lima Declaration, as previously announced.
On the official ASPA website, it can be verified that the document was published last March.
At both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities tried to set up secure transmission systems for all journalists, but they limited the access to information to the maximum extent possible.
The summit also concluded with Chile and Peru jointly agreeing to accept a Hague Court ruling that settles a border dispute between the two countries.
The presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebastián Piñera, met at the regional meeting and said they respected the ICJ's decision to hear the pleadings of both sides in the case that Lima filed against Santiago and which starts on Monday in The Hague.
"We will respect and implement the verdict that will resolve the disputes we are bringing before this international court today", declared President Humala, alongside his Chilean counterpart.
"Chile has always been, and will continue to be, a country that respects international law, the peaceful resolution of disputes, treaties and international courts", added President Piñera as he shook hands with President Humala, alongside flags of both countries.
The two presidents' confirmation that they would submit to the ICJ came after Colombia denounced this week the Bogota Pact by which it had agreed to submit to the decisions of this international court, after a decision on the maritime borders with Nicaragua that it considered to be gravely wrong.
The summit was held without the presence of the presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rouseff, Venezuela, Hugo Chávez, Bolivia, Evo Morales, and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, suspended from Unasur since 2011 after the dismissal of its former president Fernando Lugo, did not participate in the meeting.
The host president, Ollanta Humala, was given the task of opening the deliberations in the morning and closing the summit shortly after noon in Lima.
The Commissioner read out the final document in which he announced that 16 agreements had been adopted and that the lines of action for 31 projects had been established between the South American countries for a total of 17 million dollars of investment.
Among the agreements adopted, he mentioned that the Unasur countries would make "important steps to achieve the goal of South American citizenship through the development of agreements on residence permits".
He informed that actions would be put in place to improve "cooperation in the fight against urban insecurity and international organized crime, actions for better access to medicines, access to low-cost Internet throughout South America, and to jointly and effectively assess the risks of natural disasters".
With Europe in crisis, "economic consolidation (of Latin America) must not have a triumphalist matrix but must help to increase our productive matrix and to envision a better future for our peoples", President Humala concluded.
"We have decided to give priority to a group of 31 emblematic projects that improve the connectivity of the spaces of South America, especially in rural and border areas ... by uniting our countries and generating new economic circuits", the Peruvian president said in a speech.
Of these projects, he mentioned that five concerned Peru and were located on the cross-sections of its territory, from the coast to Brazil, and that two aimed at a larger connection with Ecuador, although he did not give the most extensive details.
The final document also mentions the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the electoral process in this country will allow its reintegration into the Union of South American Nations", from which it is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain a region of peace and prosperity, integrated and in good relations with its neighbours, was another theme addressed at the summit.
In this sense, the Colombian President, Juan Manuel Santos, said, before starting the regional meeting, that he hoped to meet his Nicaraguan counterpart, Daniel Ortega, the following Saturday in Mexico City to calmly discuss the maritime dispute through an ICJ ruling requested by Bogota.
"It is possible that tomorrow (Saturday), I have a meeting with President Daniel Ortega", said President Santos.
"We will review all these ways, they are not exhaustive, including the treaty with Nicaragua which will ask for a discussion with that country", he stressed.
'I hope I can tell President Ortega that we will settle this in the most civilized and respectful way possible,' added President Santos.
Presidents Santos and Ortega will meet Saturday in Mexico City where they plan to attend the inauguration of the country's new president, Enrique Peña Nieto.
Similarly, as part of the summit, the bloc's defence ministers will meet in advance to approve the 2013 Action Plan, which seeks to strengthen dialogue and consensus in terms of defence in the region.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Suriname and Paraguay are members of Unasur, although the latter has been suspended.
Peru holds the pro tempore presidency of the regional bloc.
