AIDS-related deaths today are due to late detection.
Fabrizio was 21 when he tested positive for HIV.
"It's as if the sky had fallen on my head", he said, referring to the moment of the announcement, which the doctor had tried to make "less painful", to no avail.
The young man hid it from his family.
He decided to take charge of his illness and began to inquire about it and his determination was such that he had just celebrated his 43rd birthday.
He is, without a doubt, one of the oldest patients in the HIV unit of the Guadalajara Civil Hospital (HCG), where he found himself in 1994 after many battles.
Fabrizio has lived with the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) for 22 years, something hard to imagine in the early 1990s, when there were many doubts, few treatment options and more stigmas.
Even the director of a clinic at the IMSS refused to say good-bye to him "because he was speechless".
In those days, AIDS was a death sentence.
Today, it is possible to survive this syndrome and to have a good quality of life.
However, unaware of their illness, many people still arrive when the virus has already caused damage, "worn out" their immune systems and fall victim to opportunistic infections.
Thirty-one years after the emergence of AIDS in the world, in any case after the first reported cases, "the great victory today is that the survival of a patient who started treatment at the right time and the survival of the population in general is exactly the same", said the head of the HCG HIV unit, Jaime Andrade Villanueva, and he takes as a reference that this information was validated in April of this year in a prestigious scientific publication.
Infectious disease specialist and HIV/AIDS expert Andrade Villanueva commented that since 2008, scientists have concluded that AIDS is no longer a fatal disease, but that the number of years of survival and quality of life depends on the level of immune system damage that patients present at the time of diagnosis, with better prospects for those not using drugs: up to 30 years for those with a CD4 count of 200 and up to 50 years for those with a CD4 count of 500.
Simply put, this means that if someone is diagnosed as HIV positive at the age of 25, "as long as they remain under control, they can live without problems until they are 75", the scientist said.
To put this progress in context, it is important to note that the average life expectancy of Mexicans is now 76 years.
While it is true that mortality has decreased significantly in recent years, in the case of Mexico, the number of people who died from AIDS increased from 6,678 cases in 2007 to 4,862 in 2011 (according to the annual report of UNAIDS), but it is also true that, since the emergence of AIDS, 60% of the patients registered in the national database have died.
In Jalisco alone, 255 people died in 2011, and there were 187 deaths as of May this year; however, we are assured that access to antiretroviral drugs has been universal since 2005.
Then why are there still deaths?
I don't think the problem is access to treatment.
That's how I see it, that's what happened in our hospital.
For the last 12 years at least, we've never run out of drugs, the problem is that patients arrive at very advanced stages because they don't know they're infected, or they learn it in very advanced stages of the disease.
He gives us an indisputable fact that "nine out of ten patients arrive with an opportunistic infection, what is needed to have a greater impact on the overall mortality is to make earlier diagnoses and, for this, to offer mass testing to all those who ask for it".
The experts and members of the Jalisco State Council for the Prevention of AIDS (Coesida) agree with his proposal, as do the patients themselves, such as Fabrizio, who had to take his test in a private laboratory simply because a friend had done it and that, despite his young age, he already had AIDS and suffered from Kaposi's sarcoma, a cancerous tumor that is one of the common complications.
Everything changes when you find out you have AIDS.
Some people think they're gonna die and they don't want to know.
"If I'm going to die, I'd better have sex three times a week", they say, which I don't.
The change has been beneficial, I'm eating right, I'm exercising, I'm taking my medication.
So far, his parents only know that he has cancer.
I have a normal life, like anyone else.
"I work, I have many activities, I travel, I have an active sex life, but I am responsible, I take care of myself and the other person", says Fabrizio, who agreed to share his intimacy with MILENIO JALISCO to help, thanks to his testimony, those who are afraid today, during the march of the World Day against AIDS.
Let them get tested, if they've taken risks, the sooner they know if they're HIV positive the better, and if they've already been diagnosed, they need to know that you can live like everyone else, responsibly.
His message sums up the slogan of the battle against AIDS in this year 2012.
Condoms on the counter.
There are many gaps between health programs and the ordinary citizen, argues Ricardo Salazar, a Guadalajara journalist who has covered the HIV cause.
And the biggest one is prevention.
In all the places dedicated to this, "the distribution of condoms has actually increased, before we were given one or two, now we are given packages of a hundred, that is very good, but the result is that even today, some people do not have access to condoms", he says.
Among those most vulnerable to new infections are teenagers.
The question, "What are you going to do with it?" asked sarcastically and value-judgments by social workers, guidance counselors, pharmacists and health professionals, is the question that adolescents do not want to hear, the journalist assures.
He proposes to redirect this inefficient distribution; that condoms not only be sold at counters, but be found in the dispensers of public toilets and in places frequented by young people.
It is not about encouraging promiscuity.
Nor is it about paying them for the girls and the motel, as Governor Emilio González said when asked if there would be a condom distribution in his administration.
"That's not how sex works, the best thing is to provide condoms to people who are already sexually active", he stressed.
The figures in Jalisco
There are 13,435 cases combined (12,158 of AIDS and 1,317 of HIV).
The state is the 4th state in the country in the number of new and cumulative AIDS cases and 13th in the number of HIV patients.
92% of infections are sexually transmitted, 6% are bloodborne and 2% are perinatal.
An estimated 50,000 people are living with HIV, since for every one reported case, there are four or five people who don't know they have it.
A ruling upheld on appeal by a US court ignores the debt restructuring of the Vitro group that was agreed through a commercial bankruptcy in Mexico, setting a damaging precedent for all national companies with branches in the neighboring country and solvency problems.
It seems that the survival procedures of companies authorized by Mexican laws are not valid in the country with the star-studded flag, contrary to international agreements.
From a practical point of view, the blow to the ruling delivered on June 15 by Judge Harlin Hale of the Bankruptcy Court for the Northern District of Texas leaves Mexican companies defenseless against the possibility of embargoes on their properties beyond the Bravo.
However, the resolution will allow Mexico's leading glass manufacturer to take the case to the U.S. Supreme Court on three grounds of inconsistency.
First, while the trial judge noted that creditors must register under the United States Bankruptcy Code, the Fifth Circuit Court of Appeals, sitting in New Orleans, affirmed that the principal proceeding is the commercial bankruptcy formalized in Mexico.
The first point would involve denouncing international procedural cooperation in insolvency cases involving companies with a transnational profile.
In fact, the United Nations Model Law for Uniformity in International Commercial Law was created for this purpose by taking the American Law Institute as an arbiter.
Second, the judgment states that without the intercompany vote, recognised in the critical mass of the commercial bankruptcy, the debts incurred by Vitro subsidiaries towards the parent company, the majority required for approval of the restructuring could not have been obtained.
However, Mexican laws recognize this possibility.
In fact, Vitro's case isn't the first to use this plan.
Here are half a dozen examples, including Agremex and Comercial Mexicana, whose debts were guaranteed by the Federal Institute of Commercial Insolvency.
Furthermore, what is certain is that, since the subsidiaries' votes were left, in any case the Vitro creditors who fought against this in the US courts, i.e. the "vault" funds such as Aurelios Capital, Aurelios Convergencia, Elliot Internacional and Liverpool Limited, would not have obtained a majority.
The vote would have been 45 to 37.
A fact the appeals court omitted.
On the other hand, Vitro was blamed for the difficult situation it had been facing since 2008 without addressing the severe economic crisis facing the United States, which was spilling over costs to the country.
For the time being, the González Sada family company will appeal to the same appellate court to have the vote taken in its entirety, that is, with the five magistrates, since only three had voted.
The insurance appeal will claim non-prosperity and require review of the case by a higher court, in this case the United States Supreme Court of Justice.
The most serious is that the court ignored a document sent by the Mexican government on behalf of the amicus curiae ("friend of the court") detailing the procedure followed by Vitro under the Commercial Bankruptcy Act, stating that this freed it from the agreements signed by both countries to bring it up to the same level as paragraph 15 of the US Bankruptcy Act.
It also points out that the country has complied with the principles of the United Nations Commission on International Trade, i.e. the rules laid down for cross-border insolvency cases, which guarantee fairness for debtors and creditors.
Two-part mix-up: they beat Vitro and they beat the country.
