The death of actor Larry Hagman
Larry Hagman, born September 21, 1931, in Fort Worth, Texas, became world famous for playing the lead role of John Ross Ewing, better known as J.R., in the television series "Dallas", in which he played a ruthless, fearful, and manipulative businessman.
Larry Hagman, whose role as the unscrupulous oil tycoon J.R. Ewing in the television series "Dallas" became a symbol of greed in the 1980s, has died.
He was 81.
Hagman, who returned this year as J.R. in a new season of "Dallas", died Friday night of complications from cancer, according to a family statement sent to The Associated Press for Warner Bros., the production house of "Dallas".
"Larry was back in his beloved hometown of Dallas, playing the ironic role he loved most", the family said.
Larry's family and close friends were with him in Dallas on this Thanksgiving holiday.
Linda Gray, who played his wife in the original series and in the sequel, was with Hagman when he died in a Dallas hospital, said his press secretary, Jeffrey Lane.
He brought joy to all who knew him.
He was creative, generous, funny, affectionate and talented, and he will be sorely missed.
"He was an exceptional person and he lived life to the fullest", Gray said in a statement.
Doctors had diagnosed Larry Hagman with cirrhosis of the liver in 1992 and he had admitted to having been a heavy drinker for many years.
In 1995, he was diagnosed with a malignant tumor in his liver and underwent a transplant.
Several years before "Dallas", Hagman had made his name in television as an ordinary guy in the NBC series "The Ginny of My Dreams" from 1965 to 1970.
In it, he played Captain Tony Nelson, an astronaut whose life is transformed when he discovers a seductive genius, played by Barbara Eden, and brings her home.
He also starred in two short-lived sitcoms, "The Good Life" (NBC, 1971-72) and "Here We Go Again" (ABC, 1973).
His film credits include critically acclaimed roles in The Group, Harry and Tonto, and Primary Colors.
But it was his masterful portrayal of the deliciously obnoxious J.R. that Larry Hagman's greatest success.
The CBS drama series about the Ewing family and their relatives ran from April 1978 to May 1991.
The "Who killed J.R.?" slogan, invented to maintain suspense around an emotional episode in which Hagman's character is nearly murdered, has generated worldwide speculation and millions of dollars in gambling.
This, among other things, helped the series set a record for the time.
When the answer was revealed in a November 1980 episode, an average of 41 million viewers watched the show, making "Dallas" the second most-watched entertainment program in the world, behind the final episode of "MASH" in 1983, which drew 50 million viewers.
It was J.R.'s sister-in-law, Kristin (played by Mary Crosby) who shot him.
J.R. had got her pregnant and then threatened to charge her with prostitution if she didn't leave town, but other people had reasons to attack her, too.
Hagman played Ewing as a corrupt and insatiable but charismatically smiling man: a dishonest contractor and an unfaithful husband who tried to get his alcoholic wife Sue Ellen (Linda Gray) committed.
"I know what would be the epitaph for J.R"., Hagman said in 1988.
We should write, "Here lives the good citizen J.R. Ewing".
This is the only part of him that's missing.
Victoria Principal, co-star of the original series, recalled Hagman as a man "huge, both on the small screen and in life".
He is unforgettable, and irreplaceable, to millions of fans around the world, and in the hearts of all of us who have had the good fortune to know and love him.
