A class on the "End of the World" just started.
Each week, students explore apocalyptic themes such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs, and global warming.
This semester, when religion professor Stuart Charmé decided to teach a class on the end of the world, he knew he was throwing an irresistible hook: the end of the "great recount" of the Mayan calendar on December 21, which many refer to as evidence of the imminent end of the world.
But Professor Charmé had no idea what lay ahead in the months ahead: catastrophic Hurricane Sandy, a fiscal cliff that some have dubbed "debt Armageddon", and a growing conflict involving Israel, the place where end-time Christian theorists thought the apocalypse would unfold.
"I didn't realize this was going to be the most apocalyptic semester I've ever had", Charmé told his students at Rutgers-Camden University in New Jersey this week.
If you analyze what's going on in the world today as if we were 30 days later and we were telling it, that was a very good time.
And we must remember that evil is good to those who believe in the apocalypse.
And he's not the only professor to give lectures on "the end of the world" this semester, which will, in theory, be the last in history.
At Temple, assistant professor Barry Vacker is teaching a course on "Media, Culture and the End of the World".
Every week, students explore apocalyptic themes such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs and global warming.
"We analyze this because these ideas proliferate over time", he said, and the way they offer hypothetical scenarios guides certain human behavior.
If nuclear weapons were to fall into the hands of terrorists, for example, a war could break out.
This month, students will analyze films with apocalyptic themes and study how they can be compared with real-life examples.
"I tried to inform my students about what was possible, probable, credible and impossible", Vacker said.
On the main campus of Pennsylvania State University, Latin American History professor Matthew Restall and his colleague Amara Solari, an assistant professor of art history and anthropology, teamed up to give a lecture, simply titled "The End of the World".
"We are adding '2012' to give us the opportunity to give the class again, in case the world doesn't disappear", said Professor Restall.
Despite the "imminent disaster", students are required to study, create projects and take their final exams.
In Pennsylvania, the final exam will be taken the day before the apocalypse, leaving students with no choice but to work "until the night of the supposed end of the world", Restall said.
The classes have proved quite popular.
"It was complete in two hours", Restall said of his high-level course, which consisted of 35 students.
We got emails several weeks before the semester started from people asking if there were still any openings.
The students, for their part, assure that the course is one of the most interesting.
"It is fascinating to me what people are able to do to comfort themselves", says Bridgid Robinson, a 23-year-old student of religion and sociology from Haddonfield, New Jersey, at Rutgers University-Camden.
For fear of the apocalypse, whether secular or religious, is only a matter of comfort, or lack of comfort.
Will Wekesa, a 25-year-old student of psychology and nursing, claims to have watched every apocalyptic movie.
"I had never heard of a course that taught this subject", he said.
I appreciate that.
But not one of the students we interviewed, let alone a teacher, told us that he believed the world would end on December 21.
"Our first project was about Mayan prophecy, and we kind of discredited it", says Julie Zegel, a 21-year-old senior at Temple from West Chester.
The Mayans never predicted the end of the world, it's just a key date on the calendar, Restall said.
But I will admit that there is an apocalyptic anxiety in Western culture, going back several centuries, that causes people to react to changes in their environment by predicting the end of the world.
The Internet has caused a surge in this speculation.
"In other parts of the world, people don't think about that", he says.
This is predominantly the English-speaking world.
